{"title_page": "Sonja Tomi\u0107", "text_new": "'''Sonja Tomi\u0107''' is a contemporary [[Croats|Croatian]] [[writer]], [[translator]], [[illustrator]], [[Croatian studies|croatist]], [[germanistics|germanist]] and [[radio presenter]]. She has been noted for her works in [[children's literature]] and [[travelogue (literature)|travelogue]]s.\n\n== Education ==\nBorn in [[Dubrovnik]] in 1947, she graduated [[theology]], [[mathematics]], [[germanistics]] and [[Croatian language]] and [[Croatian literature|literature]] at the [[University of Zagreb]]. She lectured [[Croatian language]] for foreigners and both [[mathematics]] and [[physics]] at the monastic gymnasium Marianum, as well as [[German]] at the XVIII gymnasium in Zagreb and at the Catholic Faculty of Theology of the University of Zagreb.\n\n== Work ==\nShe is a member of the [[Croatian Writers' Association]]. She writes for ''[[Kolo (magazine)|Kolo]]''<ref> Tomi\u0107, Sonja. [http://www.matica.hr/kolo/295/Daj%20da.../ Daj da...], ''[[Kolo (magazine)|Kolo]]'' 3 (2004). Acces date 2nd April 2020. </ref>, ''[[Glas Koncila]]''<ref> Tomi\u0107, Sonja. [https://www.glas-koncila.hr/kako-je-mali-roko-duda-postao-veliki-fra-bonaventura/ Sje\u0107anje na znamenitog bibli\u010dara i povremenog Makovca] ''Glas koncila''. Published 3rd September 2012. Acces date 2nd April 2020. </ref>, ''Kana'', ''Veritas'', as well for children magazines ''Smib'', ''Zvrk'' and ''Mak''. She is an editor of children radio emissions at the [[Croatian Radio]], [[Croatian Catholic Radio]] and [[Radio Maria]].\nHer literary works were translated in [[Slovakian language|Slovakian]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[German language|German]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]], partially by her. Her husband Stjepan is also writer and co-author of two works. She collaborated with [[Stjepan Lice]], [[Bonaventura Duda]], [[Ivanka Bra\u0111a\u0161evi\u0107]] and other noted Croatian Catholic writers and intelectuals.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://verbum.hr/autori/tomic-sonja Short biography] at the verbum.hr\n* [https://hkr.hkm.hr/redakcije/djecji-program/ Childrens' Programm] of the [[Croatian Catholic Radio]]\n* [https://hrcak.srce.hr/search/?show=results&stype=1&c%5B0%5D=article_search&t%5B0%5D=Sonja+Tomi%C4%87 List of scientific articles thematizing Sonja Tomi\u0107's literary work] at the Hr\u010dak - Portal of Croatian scientific and professional journals\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2=Croatia |portal3=Children's literature|portal4=Radio|portal5=Catholicism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomi\u0107, Sonja}}\n[[Category:Woman]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dubrovnik]]\n[[Category:University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croatian writers]]\n[[Category:Croatian translators]]\n[[Category:Croatian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Children's literature]]\n[[Category:Radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Germanists]]\n[[Category:Croatian Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sonja Tomi\u0107''' is a contemporary [[Croats|Croatian]] [[writer]], [[translator]], [[illustrator]], [[Croatian studies|croatist]], [[germanistics|germanist]] and [[radio presenter]]. She has been noted for her works in [[children's literature]] and [[travelogue (literature)|travelogue]]s.\n\n== Education ==\nBorn in [[Dubrovnik]] in 1947, she graduated [[theology]], [[mathematics]], [[germanistics]] and [[Croatian language]] and [[Croatian literature|literature]] at the [[University of Zagreb]]. She lectured [[Croatian language]] for foreigners and both [[mathematics]] and [[physics]] at the monastic gymnasium Marianum, as well as [[German]] at the XVIII gymnasium in Zagreb and at the Catholic Faculty of Theology of the University of Zagreb.\n\n== Work ==\nShe is a member of the [[Croatian Writers' Association]]. She writes for ''[[Kolo (magazine)|Kolo]]''<ref> Tomi\u0107, Sonja. [http://www.matica.hr/kolo/295/Daj%20da.../ Daj da...], ''[[Kolo (magazine)|Kolo]]'' 3 (2004). Acces date 2nd April 2020. </ref>, ''[[Glas Koncila]]''<ref> Tomi\u0107, Sonja. [https://www.glas-koncila.hr/kako-je-mali-roko-duda-postao-veliki-fra-bonaventura/ Sje\u0107anje na znamenitog bibli\u010dara i povremenog Makovca] ''Glas koncila''. Published 3rd September 2012. Acces date 2nd April 2020. </ref>, ''Kana'', ''Veritas'', as well for children magazines ''Smib'', ''Zvrk'' and ''Mak''. She is an editor of children radio emissions at the [[Croatian Radio]], [[Croatian Catholic Radio]] and [[Radio Maria]].\nHer literary works were translated in [[Slovakian language|Slovakian]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[German language|German]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]], partially by her. Her husband Stjepan is also writer and co-author of two works. She collaborated with [[Stjepan Lice]], [[Bonaventura Duda]], [[Ivanka Bra\u0111a\u0161evi\u0107]] and other noted Croatian Catholic writers and intelectuals.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://verbum.hr/autori/tomic-sonja Short biography] at the verbum.hr\n* [https://hkr.hkm.hr/redakcije/djecji-program/ Childrens' Programm] of the [[Croatian Catholic Radio]]\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2=Croatia |portal3=Children's literature|portal4=Radio|portal5=Catholicism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomi\u0107, Sonja}}\n[[Category:Woman]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dubrovnik]]\n[[Category:University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croatian writers]]\n[[Category:Croatian translators]]\n[[Category:Croatian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Children's literature]]\n[[Category:Radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Germanists]]\n[[Category:Croatian Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Mudroslov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonja_Tomi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Kalypso Media", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Companies|date=October 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name\t\t= Kalypso Media GmbH\n| logo\t\t= [[Image:Kalypso Media logo.png|250px|Kalypso Media logo]]\n| type\t\t= Games publisher & developer\n| foundation\t\t= 2006\n| location\t\t= [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], [[Germany]]\n| key_people\t\t= Simon Hellwig<br />Stefan Marcinek\n| industry\t\t= [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products\t\t=\n| revenue\t\t= \n| net_income\t\t= \n| EPS\t\t\t= \n| num_employees\t\t= 80<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gameswirtschaft.de/wirtschaft/groesste-spiele-entwickler-deutschland-2020/ |title=Die gr\u00f6\u00dften Spiele-Entwickler in Deutschland 2020 |language=de |trans-title=The largest game developers in Germany 2020 |first=Petra |last=Fr\u00f6hlich |date=10 January 2020 |website=GamesWirtschaft}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year    = 2020\n| homepage\t\t= [http://www.kalypsomedia.com www.kalypsomedia.com]\n| subsid =      \n}}\n\nThe '''Kalypso Media Group''' is a [[Germany|German]] [[Video game developer|developer]] and [[Video game publisher|publisher]] of [[video game]]s with 100 employees at seven locations throughout Germany, England, and the United States. The group includes: Kalypso Media Group GmbH in [[Worms, Germany|Worms, DE]], Kalypso Media UK Ltd. in [[Bracknell|Bracknell UK]], Kalypso Media USA Inc. in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey|Ridgewood, USA]], Kalypso Media Digital Ltd. in [[Leicester|Leicester, UK]], as well as the 2015-founded Kalypso Media Mobile in [[Hamburg|Hamburg, DE]]. \n\nThe company has three in-house development studios: Realmforge Studios, Gaming Minds Studios, and Claymore Game Studios. The products of the Kalypso Media Group include the ''[[Tropico]]'', ''[[Sudden Strike]]'', ''[[Dungeons (video game)|Dungeons]]'' and ''[[Railway Empire]]'' series as well as many more.\n\n== History ==\nThe Kalypso Media Group was founded in the summer of 2006 by Simon Hellwig and Stefan Marcinek in [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]. Just one year later, a branch was opened in [[Bracknell|Bracknell, UK]], and in June 2009, another in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey|Ridgewood, USA]]. 2009, the group opened its second UK outlet in the form of Kalypso Media Digital Ltd. in [[Leicester]]. Kalypso Media Digital Ltd. is responsible for the online marketing of its own games and the products of other providers.\n\nIn November 2008, it founded the subsidiary Realmforge Studios GmbH, based in [[Munich]], and integrated Boxed Dreams, developer of ''[[Ceville]]''.  After the well known video game developer [[Ascaron]] filed for bankruptcy in June 2009, Gaming Minds Studios GmbH was incorporated by the Kalypso Media Group, and added 15 former [[Ascaron]] employees to the studio\u2019s roster. Kalypso Media Group also acquired the rights to many of Ascaron's games, and also handed these development duties to Gaming Minds Studios.  In July 2010, Berlin manufacturer The Games Company filed for bankruptcy and in September, Kalypso Media Group took over, acquiring several brands owned by the insolvent company.  Following this, Kalypso Media Group also took on 17 employees of The Games Company and its studio [[Silver Style Entertainment]], moving operations to a newly founded Berlin outlet, [[Noumena Studios]] . In 2014, [[Noumena Studios]] was renamed Skilltree Studios and in 2016, it closed its doors.\n\nFrom March 2013 to August 2014, the Kalypso Media Group released its own intermittent podcast called the KalypsoCast.  From November 2013 and the podcast\u2019s eleventh edition, an accompanying video version was uploaded to Youtube. Regular guests on the KalypsoCast included former Kalypso Media Group CEO Stefan Marcinek, PR manager Bernd Berheide, and producers and product managers Christian Schl\u00fctter, Timo Thomas and Dennis Blumenthal. In April 2014, Kalypso Media Mobile GmbH was founded in [[Berlin]]. The studio\u2019s first mobile and tablet games were released a year later in May 2015.\n\nIn January 2016, Stefan Marcinek sold his shares in the Kalypso Media Group and left the company, leaving Simon Hellwig as sole shareholder.\n\nSince July 2018, all rights to the titles of [[Pyro Studios]] ([[Commandos (series)|''Commandos'']], ''[[Imperial Glory]]'', [[Praetorians (video game)|''Praetorians'']]) have been added to the Kalypso Media Group\u2019s portfolio.\n\n== Subsidiaries ==\nKalypso maintains several of its own development studios:\n* Realmforge Studios was established in Munich in 2008 incorporating the team of Boxed Dreams who had developed ''[[Ceville]]''. Realmforge oversees development on the ''[[Dungeons (video game)|Dungeons]]'' series of games\n* Gaming Minds Studios was established in [[G\u00fctersloh]] in June 2009 following the bankruptcy of [[Ascaron]], incorporating fifteen Ascaron developers into the team. Gaming Minds develops games in the ''[[Railway Empire]]'' and ''[[Port Royale: Gold, Power and Pirates|Port Royale]]'' series.\n* Claymore Game Studios was established in [[Darmstadt]] in December 2019, and is working on a new game in the [[Commandos (series)|''Commandos'']] series.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mcvuk.com/business-news/kalypso-media-opens-new-studio-in-frankfurt/ | title = Kalypso Media opens new studio in Frankfurt | first =Vikki | last = Blake | date = 11 December 2019 | accessdate = 2 April 2020 | work = [[MCVUK]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-04-02-third-internal-kalypso-studio-revealed-as-claymore-game-studios | title = Third internal Kalypso studio revealed as Claymore Game Studios | first = Matthew | last = Handrahan | date = 2 April 2020 | accessdate = 2 April 2020 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\n== Notable games published ==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! Release date \t\n! Title \t\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[Spacebase Startopia]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[Port Royale 4]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n|2020\n|Immortal Realms: Vampire Wars\n|\n|-\n| 2019\t\n| [[Tropico 6]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2018\t\n| [[Shadows: Awakening]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2018\t\n| [[Railway Empire]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2017\t\n| [[Dungeons 3]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2017\t\n| [[Vikings: Wolves of Midgard]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2017\t\n| [[Sudden Strike 4]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2017\t\n| [[Urban Empire]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2015\t\n| [[Crookz: The Big Heist]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2015 \t\n| [[Grand Ages: Medieval]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2015\t\n| [[Dungeons 2]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2014\t\n| [[Tropico 5]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2013\t\n| [[Dark (video game)|Dark]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2013\t\n| [[Rise of Venice]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2013\t\n| [[Alien Spidey]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2013\t\n| [[Dollar Dash]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2013\t\n| [[Omerta - City of Gangsters]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Anna (video game)|Anna]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Sine Mora]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Legends of Pegasus]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Hard Reset|Hard Reset: Extended Edition]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Port Royale 3]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Jurassic Park: The Game]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\t\n| [[Jagged Alliance (series)#Jagged Alliance: Back in Action|Jagged Alliance: Back in Action]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Global Ops: Commando Libya]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Airline Tycoon|Airline Tycoon II]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Air Conflicts: Secret Wars]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Tropico 4]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Boulder Dash|Boulder Dash XL]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Revolution Under Siege]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Patrician IV|Patrician IV: Rise of a Dynasty]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[The First Templar]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Elements of War]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Dungeons (video game)|Dungeons]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2011\t\n| [[Dungeons (video game)|Dungeons - The Dark Lord]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[Disciples III]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[Pole Position 2010]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[DarkStar One|DarkStar One: Broken Alliance (Xbox 360)]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[Patrician IV|Patrician IV: Conquest by Trade]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[Darkfall Online|Darkfall]]\t\n| Online Distribution only\t\n|-\n| 2010\t\n| [[M.U.D. TV]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2009\t\n| [[Tropico 3]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2009\t\n| [[Time of Shadows]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2009\t\n| [[Dawn of Magic 2]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2009\t\n| [[Ceville]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2009\t\n| [[Grand Ages: Rome]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2008\t\n| [[Winter Challenge 2008]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2008\t\n| [[AGON|AGON - The Lost Sword of Toledo]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2008\t\n| [[Imperium Romanum (video game)|Imperium Romanum]]\t\n|\n|-\n| 2008\t\n| [[The Political Machine 2008|Political Machine 2008]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2008\t\n| [[Racing Team Manager (video game)|Racing Team Manager]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2007\t\n| [[Jack Keane (video game)|Jack Keane]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2007\t\n| [[Hollywood Pictures 2 (video game)|Hollywood Pictures 2]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2007\t\n| [[Campus (video game)|Campus]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2007\t\n| [[Star Assault (video game)|Star Assault]]\t\n|\t\n|-\n| 2007\t\n| [[Theatre of War (video game)|Theatre of War]]\t\n|\t\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|www.kalypsomedia.com}}\n\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Companies|date=October 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name\t\t= Kalypso Media GmbH\n| logo\t\t= [[Image:Kalypso Media logo.png|250px|Kalypso Media logo]]\n| type\t\t= Games publisher & developer\n| foundation\t\t= 2006\n| location\t\t= [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], [[Germany]]\n| key_people\t\t= Simon Hellwig<br />Stefan Marcinek\n| industry\t\t= [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products\t\t=\n| revenue\t\t= \n| net_income\t\t= \n| EPS\t\t\t= \n| num_employees\t\t= 80<ref>{{cite web |url=https://