{"title_page": "The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name        = The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set\n| type        = box\n| artist      = [[Henry Cow]]\n| cover       = HenryCow AlbumCover HCBox40thAnniv.jpg\n| released    = {{Start date|2009|1}}\n| recorded    = 1972\u20131978\n| genre       = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Avant-rock]]\n*[[free improvisation]]\n}}\n| length      = {{Duration|m=596|s=28}} <small>(excluding bonus CD)</small>\n| label       = [[Recommended Records|Recommended]] (UK)\n| producer    = [[Henry Cow]]\n| prev_title  = [[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]\n| prev_year   = 2008\n| next_title  = The Henry Cow Box Redux: The Complete Henry Cow\n| next_year   = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set''''' (also known as '''''The Road''''') is a nine-CD plus one-DVD limited edition<ref>1500 copies (box set liner notes).</ref> [[box set]] by English [[avant-rock]] group [[Henry Cow]], and was released by [[Recommended Records|R\u0113R Megacorp]] in January 2009. It consists of almost 10 hours of previously unreleased recordings made between 1972 and 1978 from concerts, radio broadcasts, one-off projects, events and the studio. Included are new compositions, over four hours of [[free improvisation]], and live performances of some of Henry Cow's original LP repertoire.\n\n[[Chris Cutler]], of Henry Cow and [[Recommended Records]], planned and coordinated the whole project. Assembly of the recordings began in the mid-1990s and were edited by Cutler. He also prepared and edited two books that are included in the box set. [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]] [[remaster]]ed and, where possible, non-invasively [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|remixed]] the original recordings at Studio Midi-Pyrenees in France between 2004 and 2008.\n\nThe box set was expected to be ready before the end of 2008 to coincide with the 40th anniversary of the formation of Henry Cow, but the discovery of additional material delayed its release. Volume 6 of the box set, ''[[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'' was released separately by R\u0113R Megacorp in September 2008 in advance of the box set's release. A limited edition bonus CD, ''A Cow Cabinet of Curiosities'' was given to subscribers of the box set.\n\nIn March 2017 Volumes 1 to 5 and 7 to 10 of the box set, plus the bonus CD were each released by R\u0113R Megacorp as separate albums.\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[All About Jazz]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=AllmusicP1/><ref name=AllmusicP2/>\n| rev3 = Dusted\n| rev3Score = favourable<ref name=Dusted/>\n}}\n{{Quote box | quote  = \"[This is] one of the best collections ever released about a group that most people have never heard.\" | source = John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]].<ref name=AllAboutJazz>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/the-40th-anniversary-henry-cow-box-set-by-john-kelman.php |title=Henry Cow: The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |website=[[All About Jazz]] |first=John |last=Kelman |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=24 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730211951/https://www.allaboutjazz.com/henry-cow-the-40th-anniversary-henry-cow-box-set-by-john-kelman.php |archivedate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> | width = 22em <!-- to match {{Album ratings}} -->| align  = right}}\n\nIn a review of this box set, John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]] said that it \"offers, for the first time, a comprehensive account of Henry Cow's breadth and depth.\" He went on to say that \"If ever there were a group with a wrong to be righted, it would have to be Henry Cow. With a wellspring of unreleased material, an impressive editing and mastering job that's made even audience cassette recordings sound crystal clear, ... ''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set'' is the set die-hard fans have been waiting for.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> This review was listed at position 3 in All About Jazz's \"Top 50 Most Recommended CD Reviews\" for 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/yearend_article_recommended.php?this_year=2009&article_type=100 |title=Top 50 Most Recommended CD Reviews: 2009 |website=[[All About Jazz]] |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] described the box set as a \"monument\" and a \"treasure trove\".<ref name=AllmusicP1>{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=the-road-vols-1-5-mw0001928009|pure_url=yes}} |title=Henry Cow: The Road, Vols. 1\u20135 |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Couture |accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> He said that it \"present[s] for the first time a complete picture of Henry Cow, from the rehearsal-intensive compositions to the ever-important improvisations, through all incarnations of the band and including both highs and lows.\"<ref name=AllmusicP2>{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=10-road-40th-anniversary-box-set-6-mw0001272127|pure_url=yes}} |title=Henry Cow: The Road, Vols. 6\u201310 |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Couture |accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> ''Dusted Magazine'' said that the set \"fills in many missing historical and compositional links\" and that it is a \"fitting monument to one of the most interesting and eclectic groups to come out of the 1970s.\"<ref name=Dusted>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/5258 |title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |last=Medwin |first=Marc |date=25 September 2009 |magazine=Dusted Magazine |accessdate=6 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124143/http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/5258 |archivedate=9 February 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe box set is split into two boxes:\n*Box 1: ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135'' consists of five CDs and a book, and covers the period 1972 to 1976. Included is the March 1976 [[Hamburg]] radio show that was [[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]]\u2019s last concert with the band, and the [[Trondheim]] concert that followed in May where Henry Cow improvised as a quartet in the dark.\n*Box 2: ''The Road: Volumes 6\u201310'' consists of four CDs, a DVD and a book, and covers the period 1976 to 1978. Included is the March 1978 [[Bremen]] radio broadcast and the May 1977 [[Sveriges Radio|Swedish Radio]] broadcast. The DVD is a 75 minute video of Henry Cow (with [[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] and [[Dagmar Krause]]) performing in Switzerland in 1976.\n\nSubscribers to this box set received a limited edition bonus CD, plus a third, empty box entitled ''The Studio: Volumes 1\u20135'' to hold the five Henry Cow studio recordings re-issued on CD by [[Recommended Records]] in the ''[[Henry Cow Box]]'' in 2006. Space was left in ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135'' box for the CD re-issue of ''[[Concerts (Henry Cow album)|Concerts]]'' (also included in the ''Henry Cow Box''). Combining the ''Henry Cow Box'' and ''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set'' gives the complete works of Henry Cow.\n\n==Box 1: ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135''==\nA 60-page book accompanies this box and contains the following:\n*Volumes 1\u20135 track notes\n*Memoirs by [[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]], [[Chris Cutler]], [[Geoff Leigh]], [[Lindsay Cooper]],{{refn|[[Lindsay Cooper]]'s contribution was taken from a collection of memoirs she had dictated to a friend between 1999 and 2001 when she could no longer use her hands due to [[multiple sclerosis]]. The notes were for a book she was working on at the time, ''The Road is Wider Than Long: Travels with MS''. [[Chris Cutler]] said that while this box set was being prepared, \"communication [with her] had become almost impossible.\"{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|pp=3,37}} Cooper died on 18 September 2013.<ref name=Fordham>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/24/lindsay-cooper |last=Fordham |first=John |title=Lindsay Cooper obituary |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 September 2013| accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Mack>{{cite web |url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/rip-lindsay-cooper-member-of-comus-and-henry-cow-collaborator |last=Mack |first=Shane |title=RIP: Lindsay Cooper, member of Comus and Henry Cow collaborator |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |date=19 September 2013| accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} [[Peter Blegvad]] and [[Dagmar Krause]]\n*Henry Cow concert list, May 1968 to August 1978{{refn|Compiled by Aymeric Leroy,<ref name=HC-chron/> and Chris Cutler.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=59}}|group=\"nb\"|name=\"HC-concerts\"}}\n----\n\n===''Volume 1: Beginnings''===\nExtracts from rehearsal and other tapes from before ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]'' (1973).\n\n\"Pre-Teenbeat I/II\" are fragments later incorporated into \"Teenbeat\". Track 6 is an extended version of \"Teenbeat\" with a lengthy guitar solo from Fred Frith and an embedded free improvisation section. \"Citizen King\" became \"[[Nine Funerals of the Citizen King]]\", and \"Nirvana for Moles\" became \"Nirvana for Mice\" on ''Legend''. \"Rapt in a Blanket\" and \"Came to See You\" are two songs composed and sung by Frith around arrangements by Henry Cow. Frith had presented the songs to the group as just chords and a tune and in need of elaboration, which forced the band to adjust their approach from only working on longish instrumentals. At the time Chris Cutler had been rehearsing part-time with Henry Cow, and he has stated that it was this new challenge which prompted him to join the group permanently.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=4}}\n\n''With the Yellow Half-Moon and Blue Star'' is a Frith composition that was commissioned by the Cambridge Contemporary Dance Group under Liebe Klug, and was named after a painting by [[Paul Klee]] (''Avec la demi-lune jaune et l'\u00e9toile bleue'').{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=7}} Only an extract of it appeared on ''Legend'', whereas it is featured here for the first time in its entirety. ''Guider Tells of Silent Airborne Machine'' is a suite of three instrumentals, \"Olwyn Grainger\" and \"Betty McGowan\" by the group and \"Lottie Hare\" (\"a neo-classical miniature\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>) by John Greaves. Its inspiration came from a news item that appeared on 23 August 1971 in ''[[The Times]]'' about a group of [[Girl Guiding and Girl Scouting|Girl Guide]] leaders, Olwyn Grainger, Lottie Hare and Betty McGowan who had reported witnessing a [[Unidentified flying object|UFO]].{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=9}}\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Pre-Teenbeat I\n| writer1 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 1:44\n| title2 = Pre-Teenbeat II\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 1:28\n| title3 = Rapt in a Blanket\n| writer3 = Frith\n| length3 = 5:06\n| title4 = Came to See You\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 6:43\n| title5 = Amygdala extract (pre-''Legend'' demo)\n| writer5 = [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 3:35\n| title6 = Teenbeat\n| writer6 = Frith\n| length6 = 10:19\n| title7 = [[Nine Funerals of the Citizen King|Citizen King]]\n| writer7 = Hodgkinson\n| length7 = 5:21\n| title8 = Nirvana for Moles\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 4:09\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''With the Yellow Half-Moon and Blue Star''\n| title9 = Introduction\n| writer9 = Frith\n| length9 = 0:46\n| title10 = Invocation\n| writer10 = Frith\n| length10 = 2:08\n| title11 = Demi-Lune Jaune\n| writer11 = Frith\n| length11 = 2:10\n| title12 = Three Little Steps\n| writer12 = Frith\n| length12 = 2:13\n| title13 = Red Riff\n| writer13 = Frith\n| length13 = 1:50\n| title14 = Chorale Flautando\n| writer14 = Frith\n| length14 = 1:51\n| title15 = Cycling over the Cliff\n| writer15 = Frith\n| length15 = 4:08\n| title16 = First Light\n| writer16 = Frith\n| length16 = 0:51\n}}{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Guider Tells of Silent Airborne Machine''\n| total_length = 64:22\n| 