erspaced with improvisations by the group.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} Part of another performance of this suite also features in \"Groningen\" on ''[[Concerts (Henry Cow album)|Concerts]]'' (1976). Halsteren concert organiser Jan Smagge recounts in the box set booklets an anecdote where the band were approached by several people during an interval and asked whether they could play any songs by [[Mud (band)|Mud]], a contemporary mainstream pop act.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} ''Halsteren'' is followed here by \"Living in the Heart of the Beast\" from a Paris concert with [[Robert Wyatt]] in May 1975. It is the first live recording of the completed vocal version of the composition, and is sung by [[Dagmar Krause]], her first public appearance with the band,<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> with Wyatt accompanying her in the closing verses.\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Introduction\n| writer1 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length1 = 1:52\n| title2 = [[Ruins (instrumental)|Ruins]] I\n| writer2 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length2 = 6:35\n| title3 = Half Asleep, Half Awake\n| writer3 = [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]]\n| length3 = 4:11\n| title4 = Ruins II\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 0:59\n| title5 = Heron Shower over Hamburg\n| writer5 = Frith\n| length5 = 2:29\n| title6 = Nix\n| writer6 = \n| length6 = 0:06\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Halsteren'' <small>([[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], Frith, Greaves, [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]])</small>\n| title7 = Halsteren 1\n| writer7 = \n| length7 = 1:08\n| title8 = Solo 1\n| writer8 = Hodgkinson\n| length8 = 1:08\n| title9 = Solo Extension 1\n| writer9 = \n| length9 = 2:21\n| title10 = Halsteren 2\n| writer10 = \n| length10 = 1:24\n| title11 = Extension 1\n| writer11 = \n| length11 = 0:17\n| title12 = Halsteren 3\n| writer12 = \n| length12 = 0:52\n| title13 = First Suspension\n| writer13 = \n| length13 = 4:28\n| title14 = Extension 2\n| writer14 = \n| length14 = 2:58\n| title15 = Extension 3\n| writer15 = \n| length15 = 1:19\n| title16 = Solo 2\n| writer16 = Frith\n| length16 = 1:20\n| title17 = Solo Extension 2\n| writer17 = \n| length17 = 2:32\n| title18 = Halsteren 4\n| writer18 = \n| length18 = 0:17\n| title19 = Second Suspension\n| writer19 = \n| length19 = 2:34\n| title20 = Extension 4\n| writer20 = \n| length20 = 1:58\n| title21 = Solo 3\n| writer21 = \n| length21 = 0:49\n| title22 = Solo Extension 3\n| writer22 = Greaves\n| length22 = 3:17\n| title23 = Halsteren 5\n| writer23 = \n| length23 = 1:21\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 60:01\n| title24 = [[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\"\n#<li value=24>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 7\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 8\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 9\n| writer24 = Hodgkinson\n| length24 = 13:46\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 oboe (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), bassoon (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), piano (tracks 24\u201332)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, glass bowls and clatter (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), viola (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), piano (track 1,2), electric and acoustic guitars (tracks 7\u201323), prism (tracks 7\u201323), xylophone (tracks 24\u201332)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar, piano (track 3), clothes pegs (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice (tracks 24\u201332)\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Robert Wyatt]] \u2013 voice (tracks 29,32)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20135 were recorded on the [[John Peel|John Peel Show]] in London, 25 April 1974; broadcast by the BBC 9 May 1974<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n*Tracks 7\u201323 are from a concert at the Verenigingsgebouw in [[Halsteren]], 26 September 1974, recorded by Jan Smagge on a stereo reel-to-reel\n*Tracks 24\u201332 are from a concert at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]], [[Paris]], 8 May 1975, with live mix by Sarah Greaves\n----\n\n===''Volume 3: Hamburg''===\nRecordings from Henry Cow's March 1976 [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], plus two songs with [[Robert Wyatt]] from concerts in Paris and Rome in May and June 1975, respectively.\n\n\"Fair as the Moon\", followed later by \"Terrible as an Army with Banners\" are based on \"[[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners]]\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' (1975), and became the longest lasting \"building block\" the band used in live performances.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} \"Nirvana for Rabbits\" is a rework of the Frith composition \"Nirvana for Mice\" from ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]'' (1973), while \"Ottawa Song\" is part of a longer suite Frith composed for the Ottawa Company, the rest of which never survived, except for fragments that appeared in \"Muddy Mouse\" and \"Muddy Mouth\" on Wyatt's solo album, ''[[Ruth Is Stranger Than Richard]]'' (1975).{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=13}} This performance of \"Ottawa Song\" also appears (by accident) on ''[[#Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg|Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'', but without the introductory bassoon solo. \"Gloria Gloom\" is from [[Matching Mole]]'s second album, ''[[Matching Mole's Little Red Record]]'' (1972). \"Hamburg 1\u20135\", \"Red Noise 10\" and \"A Heart\" are improvisations by the band, the last two titled at the request of NDR.{{refn|While Henry Cow generally left their improvisations untitled and referred to them by the venue they were performed at, some radio broadcasters requested that they be given titles.|group=\"nb\"|name=\"improv-titles\"}}<ref>Volume 3 CD liner notes.</ref> \"Hamburg 2\" includes a fragment from [[Slapp Happy]]'s song, \"A Little Something\".\n\nWyatt sings on \"Little Red Riding Hood Hit the Road\" from his solo album, ''[[Rock Bottom (album)|Rock Bottom]]'' (1974), and on \"We Did It Again\", a \"surprising and wackily absurdist\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> cover of the [[Soft Machine]] song from their debut album, ''[[The Soft Machine (Soft Machine album)|The Soft Machine]]'' (1968). The version of \"We Did It Again\" that appears on this CD is a combination of two different recordings of the same performance, one from an audience cassette recording with \"a lot of audience reaction, a lot of guitar, thin-sounding drums and bass, and only a faint echo of the vocals\", and one from the mixing desk with \"almost no guitar, but plenty of drums, bass, and vocals\".<ref name=BobDrake>{{cite web |url=http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/wavs/index.htm |title=Henry Cow 40th Anniversary Box Set remastering notes |first=Bob |last=Drake |authorlink=Bob Drake (musician) |accessdate=10 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220084306/http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/wavs/index.htm |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 67:44\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Fair as the Moon]]\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 6:01\n| title2 = Nirvana for Rabbits\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 4:48\n| title3 = Ottawa Song\n| writer3 = Cutler, Frith\n| length3 = 3:41\n| title4 = Twilight Bridge\n| writer4 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], Cutler, Frith, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length4 = 2:04\n| title5 = Gloria Gloom\n| writer5 = [[Robert Wyatt|Wyatt]], [[Bill MacCormick|McCormick]]\n| length5 = 2:17\n| title6 = Hamburg 1\n| writer6 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length6 = 4:15\n| title7 = Hamburg 2\n| writer7 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 3:27\n| title8 = Red Noise 10\n| writer8 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length8 = 3:16\n| title9 = Hamburg 3\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length9 = 5:30\n| title10 = Hamburg 4\n| writer10 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length10 = 2:40\n| title11 = Hamburg 5\n| writer11 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length11 = 5:25\n| title12 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Terrible as an Army with Banners]]\n| writer12 = Cutler, Frith\n| length12 = 3:34\n| title13 = A Heart\n| writer13 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length13 = 9:03\n| title14 = Little Red Riding Hood Hit the Road\n| writer14 = Wyatt\n| length14 = 5:12\n| title15 = We Did It Again\n| writer15 = [[Kevin Ayers|Ayers]]\n| length15 = 6:31\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 oboe, bassoon, flute, piano (tracks 7\u201311)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, piano (tracks 1,4,12,13)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar, voice (track 3)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Robert Wyatt]] \u2013 voice (tracks 14,15)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u201313 are from a public concert recorded for the [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop, [[Hamburg]], 26 March 1976\n*Track 14 are from a concert at the [[Piazza Navona]], [[Rome]], 27 June 1975, mixed by Sarah Greaves\n*Track 15 are from a concert at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]], [[Paris]], 8 May 1975, with live mix by Sarah Greaves\n----\n\n===''Volume 4\u20135: Trondheim''===\nA double CD of a complete concert recorded in [[Trondheim]], [[Norway]] on 26 May 1976, later broadcast on the [[Sveriges Radio]] radio program, ''Tonkraft'' on 14 July 1976.\n\nWhen Henry Cow prepared to embark on their May 1976 tour of [[Scandinavia]], they were two members short: John Greaves had left the band after the March 1976 [[Hamburg]] concert, and Dagmar Krause had remained behind in Hamburg due to ill-health. As they were committed to the tour, Henry Cow, as a quartet of Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson and Cooper, abandoned their familiar [[set list]]s and decided improvise all the concerts on the tour in the dark. They were also accompanied by \"shadows that were not us\",{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=15}} which were two-hour tapes that Cooper, Hodgkinson and Frith had each prepared. The subject of the tapes were: Cooper \u2013 youth to old age; Hodgkinson \u2013 history of language; and Frith \u2013 history of Henry Cow. The tapes ran continuously and inaudibly throughout the duration of the show, but were made audible by their creators from time to time with a foot pedal, without knowing what part of the tape would be heard. Chris Cutler explained that it was an \"attempt to inhabit a dramaturgy anchored in narratives of origins, evolution, history and ritual\".{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=15}} They also decided to disguise and \"primitivise\" themselves and their equipment, and hence the darkness.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=15}}\n\nFran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] called ''Trondheim'' the \"crown jewel\" of the box set, saying it was \"some of [Henry Cow's] darkest and most thrilling music\".<ref name=AllmusicP1/> John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]] described ''Trondheim'' as \"about as unapproachable as Henry Cow ever got, and yet amongst the densities and at times harsh realms are moments of profound beauty. The 80-minute improvisation ... demonstrates the kind of intuitive push-and-pull that could only come from musicians not just spending a great deal of time playing together, but also living together, with a potent ability to sometimes shift ambience and color at the drop of a dime.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| headline  = Disk 1\n| total_length = 48:25\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Trondheim I\"\n#<li value=1>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 7\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 8\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 9\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 10\n| writer1 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 48:25\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline  = Disk 2\n| total_length = 38:19\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Trondheim II\"\n#<li value=1>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\n| writer1 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length1 = 31:54\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith arr. [[Henry Cow]]\n| length7 = 6:25\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 oboe, bassoon, tapes, voice, flute (CD 1), recorder (CD 1), piano (CD 1, tracks 7\u20139), jaw harp (CD 2)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, telephone mouthpieces, amplification, flotsam (CD 1), voice (CD 1), jetsam (CD 2), piano (CD 2)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, 6-string bass guitar, xylophone, tapes, violin (CD 1), tubular bells (CD 1),\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, clarinet, voice, tapes, alto saxophone (CD 2), mbira (CD 2)\n\n====Track notes====\n*All tracks from a cassette recording made by Henry Cow at the mixing desk at a concert at Studentersamfundet, [[Trondheim]], 26 May 1976, mixed by Joel Schwartz\n\n==Box 2: ''The Road: Volumes 6\u201310''==\nA 60-page book accompanies this box and contains the following:\n*Volumes 6\u201310 track notes\n*Memoirs by [[Nick Hobbs]], [[Franco Fabbri]], [[Georgina Born]], [[Fred Frith]], [[Chris Wangro]] and [[Tim Hodgkinson]]\n*Post Henry Cow collaborations\n*A summary economic history of Henry Cow\n*Appendix 1: Equipment \u2013 PA system, studio, vehicles{{refn|Taken from documents written by Nick Hobbs that were included with Henry Cow's application for support from the [[Arts Council of Great Britain|Arts Council]].{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=19}}|group=\"nb\"}}\n*Appendix 2: 1977 Henry Cow accounts\n*Appendix 3: Extract from the Henry Cow Weekly Meeting Minute Book, 13 December 1976, [[Trappes]]\n----\n\n===''Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg''===\n{{main|Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg}}\n[[Sveriges Radio|Swedish Radio]] recordings of concerts performed in May 1976 in [[Gothenburg]] and May 1977 in [[Stockholm]]. This CD was released separately from the box set by R\u0113R Megacorp in September 2008.\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 63:23\n| title1 = Stockholm 1\n| writer1 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 6:38\n| title2 = [[Erk Gah]]\"\n#<li value=2>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\n| writer2 = Hodgkinson\n| length2 = 17:06\n:3:28\n:2:55\n:2:27\n:6:17\n:1:59\n| title7 = A Bridge to Ruins\n| writer7 = Hodgkinson\n| length7 = 5:08\n| title8 = Ottawa Song\n| writer8 = Cutler, Frith\n| length8 = 3:27\n| title9 = G\u00f6teborg 1\"\n#<li value=9>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length9 = 16:53\n:6:06\n:8:20\n:2:27\n| title12 = No More Songs\n| writer12 = [[Phil Ochs|Ochs]] arr. Frith\n| length12 = 3:35\n| title13 = Stockholm 2\n| writer13 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length13 = 6:13\n| title14 = March\n| writer14 = Frith\n| length14 = 4:15\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello (tracks 1\u20137,12\u201314)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, flute, recorder, piano (tracks 1\u20132), tapes (tracks 9-11)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, electrification, piano (track 10)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, xylophone, tapes (tracks 9-11), piano (tracks 13\u201314)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, voice (tracks 9-11), tapes (tracks 9-11)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 singing (tracks 1\u20137,12\u201314)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar (track 8), voice (track 8)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20137 and 12\u201314 were recorded for ''Tonkraft'' by [[Sveriges Radio]] at a concert in [[Stockholm]] on 9 May 1977 and broadcast on 8 June and 11 June 1977; the programme producer was S. Vermalin\n*Track 8 was recorded for the [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop in [[Hamburg]] on 26 March 1976; its inclusion in this volume was unintentional and later acknowledged (see ''[[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'')\n*Tracks 9-11 were recorded for ''Tonkraft'' by Sveriges Radio at a concert in [[Gothenburg]] on 28 May 1976 and broadcast on 14 July and 17 July 1976; the programme producer was Christer Eklund\n----\n\n===''Volume 7: Later and Post-Virgin''===\nA collection of live performances from late 1976 and 1977.\n\n\"Joan\" and \"On Suicide\", traditionally associated with [[Art Bears]] and ''[[Hopes and Fears (Art Bears album)|Hopes and Fears]]'' (1978), feature here and show that they were Henry Cow songs long before Art Bears came into being.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"On Suicide\" is longer than the Art Bears version and ends with a cello solo by [[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]]; the [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]]/[[Hanns Eisler|Eisler]] song, arranged by [[Fred Frith]], had been suggested to the group by [[Anthony Moore]].{{sfn|Piekut|2019|pp=291\u2013292}} The Art Bears version of \"Joan\" also differs from the live recording here in that it is shorter (several sections are \"telescoped\" into one), and the lyrics are not the same. [[Chris Cutler]] wrote the original lyrics for \"Joan\" and [[Tim Hodgkinson]]'s \"The Pirate Song\", but the group were unhappy with them, and the songs were withdrawn from Henry Cow's repertoire. \"Joan\" was only performed a few times, and \"The Pirate Song\" not at all. Prior to Henry Cow's recording session at Sunrise in Switzerland in January 1978, Cutler rewrote the lyrics of the two songs, but once again there were objections from factions within the group. [[Dagmar Krause]], however, supported the new lyrics and both songs were recorded by Henry Cow with the revised texts, only to be  released later by Art Bears on ''Hopes and Fears'' as a result of further disagreements with the group.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=5}}\n\n\"Untitled Piece\" was a work-in-progress by [[Lindsay Cooper]] that was only performed a few times by Henry Cow,{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=6}} and foreshadowed some of her work that appeared later on her 1998 solo album ''A View From the Bridge''.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"Chaumont 1\", \"Chaumont 2\" and \"March\" are from a Paris concert featuring an improvisation by the group, a bassoon and saxophone duet by Cooper and Hodgkinson, and Frith's familiar \"March\" to close the set. Also included are new renditions of \"Teenbeat\" and \"Bittern Storm over Ulm\". According to [[All About Jazz]], \"Teenbeat 2\" features \"some of Frith's most searing guitar playing of the box\", and \"Teenbeat 3\" has \"Hodgkinson's saxophone at its most visceral.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n\"Post-Teen Auditorium Invasion\" and \"Bucket Waltz\" are from a concert in [[Amsterdam]] that feature guests [[Annemarie Roelofs]] and ex-Henry Cow member [[Geoff Leigh]]. Roelofs, who was attending the concert, began playing trombone from the audience and was invited to join Henry Cow on stage. She ended up touring with the band the following year and playing on ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]''.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=43}} Leigh, whose band [[Red Balune]] was playing at the same concert, was invited by his former band to guest with them.<ref name=HC-chron/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 69:57\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Joan\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 5:26\n| title2 = Teenbeat 2\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 8:05\n| title3 = Would You Prefer Us to Lie?\n| writer3 = Cutler, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]]\n| length3 = 4:28\n| title4 = Untitled Piece\n| writer4 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length4 = 11:31\n| title5 = Chaumont 1\n| writer5 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], Cooper, Cutler, Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 9:01\n| title6 = Chaumont 2\n| writer6 = Cooper, Hodgkinson\n| length6 = 2:14\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith\n| length7 = 7:00\n| title8 = Brain Storm over Barnsley\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 3:23\n| title9 = Teenbeat 3\n| writer9 = Frith\n| length9 = 6:45\n| title10 = Post-Teen Auditorium Invasion\n| writer10 = Cooper, Hodgkinson, [[Geoff Leigh|Leigh]], [[Annemarie Roelofs|Roelofs]]\n| length10 = 3:56\n| title11 = Bucket Waltz\n| writer11 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, Leigh, Roelofs\n| length11 = 4:26\n| title12 = On Suicide\n| writer12 = [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]], [[Hanns Eisler|Eisler]]\n| length12 = 3:42\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet (track 12), voice (track 5), tapes\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, xylophone, tubular bells, violin, piano (track 7)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, jaw harp, flute, piano (tracks 3\u20135), accordion (track 5)\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice (track 1,3,7,12)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, contact microphone amplification (tracks 5\u20137)\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Geoff Leigh]] \u2013 tenor saxophone (tracks 10\u201311)\n*[[Annemarie Roelofs]] \u2013 trombone (tracks 10\u201311)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20133 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Wandsworth Town Hall, [[London]], 13 February 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 4 was recorded on cassette from the audience at De Plek, [[Flushing, Netherlands|Vlissingen]], 22 May 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Tracks 5\u20137 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Salle des Fetes, Chaumont, 25 November 1976, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Tracks 8\u201311 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Melkweg, [[Amsterdam]], 16 December 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 12 was from an unidentified cassette recording, probably May/June 1977\n----\n\n===''Volume 8: Bremen''===\nExtracts from a live radio broadcast on [[Radio Bremen]] for New Jazz Live on 22 March 1978.\n\nHenry Cow perform here as a [[quintet]] of Hodgkinson/Frith/Cooper/Born/Cutler; Dagmar Krause had left the band the previous November due to ill health.<ref name=HC-chron/> \"Armed Maniac/Things We Forgot\" is a titled improvisation with references \"in ambience\" to contemporary classical composers [[Krzysztof Penderecki]] and [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]].<ref group=\"nb\" name=improv-titles/><ref name=AllAboutJazz/> ''New Suite'' is a Fred Frith composition that includes \"Van Fleet\", a pun on [[Captain Beefheart|Don Van Vliet]],{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=368}} and an instrumental version of Tim Hodgkinson's \"Viva Pa Ubu\". \"Viva Pa Ubu\" is a song that had been recorded, with the whole group singing, during (what became) the ''[[Hopes and Fears (Art Bears album)|Hopes and Fears]]'' recording sessions in January 1978, and was the start of a musical production by Hodgkinson of [[Alfred Jarry]]'s play ''[[Ubu Roi]]'' (Pa Ubu being a character in the play).{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=11}} It was later released on the ''[[Recommended Records Sampler]]'' and re-released as a bonus track on the CD reissue of ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]''. ''Die Kunst Der Orgel'' is a 34-minute improvisation that ends with an instrumental version of Tim Hodgkinson's \"[[Erk Gah]]\".\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Armed Maniac/Things We Forgot\n| writer1 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 11:55\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''New Suite''\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title2 = Van Fleet\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 1:49\n| title3 = Viva Pa Ubu instrumental extract\n| writer3 = Hodgkinson\n| length3 = 4:35\n| title4 = The Big Tune Begins\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 0:45\n| title5 = The Big Tune Continues\n| writer5 = Frith\n| length5 = 2:11\n| title6 = The Big Tune Ends\n| writer6 = Frith\n| length6 = 1:30\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith\n| length7 = 3:46\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 74:00\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| headline = ''Die Kunst Der Orgel''\n| title8 = Bremen\"\n#<li value=8>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\n| writer8 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length8 = 34:25\n| title13 = Erk Gah instrumental extract\"\n:13{{ns|3}}\"Part 1\"\n:14{{ns|3}}\"Part 2\n| writer13 = Hodgkinson\n| length13 = 13:04\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, mbira, voice (track 9)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, tubular bells, marimba (track 8), xylophone (track 14), violin, piano (track 7)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, sopranino saxophone, recorder, piano (tracks 9\u201311,14), accordion, egg-slicer\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, marimba (tracks 9\u201310), piano (tracks 1,14)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Recorded for New Jazz Live at a public concert at Sendesall, Studio F, [[Radio Bremen]], 22 March 1978, produced by Bernd Meier, concert mix by Jack Balchin\n----\n\n===''Volume 9: Late''===\nA collection of performances from June and July 1978, plus Henry Cow's set at the inaugural [[Rock in Opposition|Rock in Opposition Festival]] in March 1978.\n\n\"Joy of Sax\" is a saxophone trio of Lindsay Cooper, Tim Hodgkinson and David Chambers from [[the Orckestra]], which was a merger of Henry Cow, the [[Mike Westbrook]] Brass Band and folk singer [[Frankie Armstrong]] that took place in 1977. \"Jackie-ing\", also featuring Chambers, is a Westbrook arrangement of a [[Thelonious Monk]] composition that the Orckestra had performed. \"The Herring People\" is a Fred Frith instrumental he wrote to \"counterbalance\" the increasingly complex Hodgkinson and Cooper compositions.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=9}} It was later recorded by Henry Cow during the July and August 1978 ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]'' sessions, but was only released for the first time, as \"Waking Against Sleep\", on the 1990 CD re-issue of Frith's solo album, ''[[Gravity (Fred Frith album)|Gravity]]'' (1980).{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=8}} It was also recorded by [[Curlew (band)|Curlew]] under the title \"Time and a Half\", and appeared on their album, ''North America'' (1985), which was produced by Frith.\n\nThe improvisation \"RIO\" and Cooper's \"Half the Sky\" was Henry Cow's set at the inaugural [[Rock in Opposition]] (RIO) festival that took place on 12 March 1978 at the [[New London Theatre]]. RIO was a collective of \"[[progressive rock|progressive]]\" bands that were united in their opposition to the [[music industry]]. Henry Cow initiated the movement and the other inaugural members, who also performed at the concert, were [[Stormy Six]] (Italy), [[Samla Mammas Manna]] (Sweden), [[Univers Zero]] (Belgium) and [[Etron Fou Leloublan]] (France). ''Dusted Magazine'' described Henry Cow's \"RIO\" improvisation at this event as \"one of their most cacophonous and cataclysmic\".<ref name=Dusted/>\n\nCooper's \"Half the Sky\", which had been recorded in January 1978 at Sunrise in Switzerland and was later released on ''Western Culture'', was named for [[Mao Zedong|Chairman Mao]]'s dictum \"Women hold up half the sky\".{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=8}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/GCA-Olympics/idUSSYD20777320080811|title=For Chen, women hold up half the sky|last=Hardach|first=Sophie|date=11 August 2008|website=Reuters|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref> \"Virgins of Illinois\" is another piece from the Brass Band's repertoire, and is a medley of several English folk songs that becomes a \"broad dance in three\".{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=375}} Piekut noted that the recording of \"Virgins of Illinois\" on this disc is not the complete piece as it was performed live \u2013 it stops before the song's main tune begins.{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=375}}{{sfn|Piekut|2019|loc=p. 445 (Chapter 8, footnote 70)}}\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 35:29\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Joy of Sax\n| writer1 = \n| length1 = 3:50\n| title2 = Jackie-ing\n| writer2 = [[Thelonious Monk|Monk]] arr. [[Mike Westbrook|Westbrook]]\n| length2 = 1:15\n| title3 = Untitled 2\n| writer3 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length3 = 1:32\n| title4 = The Herring People\n| writer4 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length4 = 2:07\n| title5 = RIO\"\n#<li value=5>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\n| writer5 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], Cooper, [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 17:09\n| title9 = Half the Sky\n| writer9 = Cooper\n| length9 = 5:05\n| title10 = Virgins of Illinois\n| writer10 = trad.\n| length10 = 2:13\n| title11 = Viva Pa Ubu\n| writer11 = Hodgkinson\n| length11 = 2:18\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, voice (track 7)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, violin, xylophone\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, recorder, sopranino saxophone\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Annemarie Roelofs]] \u2013 trombone (tracks 4,10)\n*[[Dave Chambers (musician)|Dave Chambers]] \u2013 saxophone (tracks 1,2)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20134,10 are from an audience recording commonly believed to be from the Festa del PdUP (Partito di Unit\u00e0 Proletaria) in Monza, Italy, 9 July 1978, though this is disputed by Chris Cutler; live concert mix by E. M. Thomas<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>; also 'disputable' is track 4, \"The Herring People\", which is believed to be an alternate mix (less reverb) of the recording \"Waking Against Sleep\" on the CD reissue [[Fred Frith]]'s ''[[Gravity (Fred Frith album)|Gravity]]'' (cd ESD 1990), credited as a studio recording from the ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]'' sessions (see this [[Talk:Henry Cow discography#\"Waking Against Sleep\"|talk page]]){{Citation required|date=January 2017}}\n*Tracks 5\u20139 are from the [[Rock in Opposition]] Festival at [[New London Theatre]], [[Drury Lane]], [[London]], 12 March 1978, recorded by Hasse Bruniusson of [[Samla Mammas Manna]], live concert mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 11 was recorded on cassette from the audience at [[Cervia]], 23 July 1978, live concert mix by E. M. Thomas\n----\n\n===''Volume 10: Vevey'' (DVD)===\nA 75-minute video of Henry Cow performing in [[Vevey]], [[Switzerland]] in August 1976, recorded for the Swiss TV program, ''Kaleidospop''.<ref name=HC-chron>{{cite web |url=http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/bands/chrono/henrycow.html |title=Henry Cow chronology |website=Calyx: The Canterbury Music Website |accessdate=9 July 2008}}</ref> This is the only known video recording of Henry Cow.<ref name=AllmusicP2/><ref>Volume 10 DVD liner notes.</ref>\n\nThe DVD features the group live outdoors on the grass and playing a set that was representative from the time. It includes [[Tim Hodgkinson]]'s two \"epic\" compositions, \"[[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\" and \"[[Erk Gah]]\", and two improvisations, \"Vevey 1\" and \"Vevey 2\".<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"Beautiful As ...\", followed later by \"Terrible As ...\" are based on \"[[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners]]\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' (1975). Fran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] described the multi-camera work on the DVD as \"pretty good\" and the editing \"dated\", but added that \"seeing the band in action, both navigating through its most complex material and engaging in collective improvisation, is quite an experience.\"<ref name=AllmusicP2/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 74:48\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Beautiful As ...]]\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 6:50\n| title2 = Vevey 1\n| writer2 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], Cutler, Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length2 = 8:49\n| title3 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Terrible As ...]]\n| writer3 = Cutler, Frith\n| length3 = 2:19\n| title4 = \n| note4 = Tim speaks\n| writer4 = \n| length4 = 1:04\n| title5 = No More Songs\n| writer5 = [[Phil Ochs|Ochs]] arr. Frith\n| length5 = 3:48\n| title6 = [[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\n| writer6 = Hodgkinson\n| length6 = 16:57\n| title7 = Vevey 2\n| writer7 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 13:51\n| title8 = March\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 2:42\n| title9 = [[Erk Gah]]\n| writer9 = Hodgkinson\n| length9 = 18:28\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, recorder, sopranino saxophone, piccolo, piano\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, violin, xylophone, piano, tubular bells\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice\n\n====Track notes====\n*Recorded 25 August 1976, [[Vevey]], [[Switzerland]], concert mixed by Joel Schwartz\n\n==Bonus CD==\n===''A Cow Cabinet of Curiosities''===\nA limited edition<ref>1000 copies (bonus CD liner notes).</ref> CD given to subscribers of the box set. The title alludes to the name of [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]]'s band, Cabinet of Curiosities.\n\n\"Pre Virgin Demo 1/2\" include fragments that were later incorporated into tracks on ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]''. \"Lovers of Gold\" is an alternate version of \"Beginning: The Long March\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' that was created by [[Chris Cutler]].<ref name=discog/> \"The Glove\" is derived from raw material recorded during the ''[[Unrest (Henry Cow album)|Unrest]]'' sessions.<ref name=discog>{{Cite web|url=http://nyds-discographies.com/frith.htm |title=Discography of Fred Frith |website=New York Downtown Scene and Other Miscellaneous Discographies |author1=Ramond, Michel |author2=Roussel, Patrice |author3=Vuilleumier, Stephane |accessdate=29 May 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619155344/http://nyds-discographies.com/frith.htm |archivedate=19 June 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 55:17\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Pre Virgin Demo 1\n| writer1 = mostly [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 3.55\n| title2 = Pre Virgin Demo 2\n| writer2 = mostly [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length2 = 1:02\n| title3 = Unidentified Improvisation 1\n| writer3 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], Frith, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]], Hodgkinson\n| length3 = 1:30\n| title4 = Unidentified Improvisation 2\n| writer4 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length4 = 5:37\n| title5 = Unidentified late composition\n| writer5 = probably Cooper\n| length5 = 2:04\n| title6 = Exploded Amygdala/Teen Introduction\n| writer6 = Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, [[Geoff Leigh|Leigh]]\n| length6 = 3:37\n| title7 = Lovers of Gold\n| writer7 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 6:29\n| title8 = Hamburg 6\n| writer8 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length8 = 5:33\n| title9 = [[Ruins (instrumental)|Ruins]] extract\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length9 = 8:24\n| title10 = Hamburg 7\n| writer10 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length10 = 9:44\n| title11 = Half the Sky\n| writer11 = Cooper\n| length11 = 5:03\n| title12 = Extract from The Glove\n| writer12 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson\n| length12 = 2:19\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 all tracks, piano (track 10), voice (track 12)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013  all tracks, voice (track 12)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 all tracks, voice (track 12)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 tracks 1\u201310,12, voice (track 12)\n*[[Geoff Leigh]] \u2013 tracks 1,2,6, voice (track 1)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 tracks 3\u20135,7\u201312, voice (track 12)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 tracks 4,8\u201310\n*[[Peter Blegvad]] \u2013 clarinet (track 7)\n*[[Anthony Moore]] \u2013 mounted and amplified tuning forks (track 7)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1,2 were recorded in Henry Cow's rehearsal space by Jack Balchin, probably 1972\n*Tracks 3\u20136 were extracted from a forgotten tape from 1975\u201377 which surfaced while this box set was being compiled<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n*Track 7 is an out-take from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' mixed by Tim Hodgkinson at Cold Storage in 1984; previously issued on the 1991 CD (remixed) edition of ''In Praise of Learning''\n*Tracks 8\u201310 were recorded at a public concert for [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop, [[Hamburg]], 26 March 1976\n*Track 11 recorded at a public concert at Sendesaal, Studio F, [[Radio Bremen]], 22 March 1978, produced by Bernd Meier\n*Track 12 is an extract from an ''[[Unrest (Henry Cow album)|Unrest]]'' out-take mixed by Tim Hodgkinson at Cold Storage in 1984; previously issued in full (6:35) on the 1991 CD edition of ''Unrest''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite AV media notes| title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |others=[[Henry Cow]] |year=2009a |chapter=The Road: Volumes 1\u20135 |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Cutler |editor-link=Chris Cutler |type=box set booklet |publisher=[[Recommended Records]] |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes| title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |others=Henry Cow |year=2009b |chapter=The Road: Volumes 6\u201310 |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Cutler |type=box set booklet |publisher=Recommended Records |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Piekut |first=Benjamin |title=Henry Cow: The World Is a Problem |title-link=Henry Cow: The World Is a Problem |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |year=2019 |isbn=978-1-47800-405-9 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|2530314|The Road: Volumes 1\u20135|type=album}}\n*{{Discogs release|1800562|The Road: Volumes 6\u201310 With DVD|type=album}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120220084240/http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/remastering.htm Henry Cow 40th Anniversary Box Set remastering notes] (including booklet corrections) by [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]].\n*[http://www.cloudsandclocks.net/interviews/CC_interview08.html Interview with Chris Cutler on the box set (2008)]. Clouds and Clocks.\n*[http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/lyrics/henrycow/01.html Henry Cow lyrics]. Calyx: The Canterbury Website.\n\n{{Henry Cow|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set, The}}\n[[Category:2009 live albums]]\n[[Category:2009 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Henry Cow albums]]\n[[Category:Recommended Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Recommended Records compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Live free improvisation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name        = The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set\n| type        = box\n| artist      = [[Henry Cow]]\n| cover       = HenryCow AlbumCover HCBox40thAnniv.jpg\n| released    = {{Start date|2009|1}}\n| recorded    = 1972\u20131978\n| genre       = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Avant-rock]]\n*[[free improvisation]]\n}}\n| length      = {{Duration|m=596|s=28}} <small>(excluding bonus CD)</small>\n| label       = [[Recommended Records|Recommended]] (UK)\n| producer    = [[Henry Cow]]\n| prev_title  = [[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]\n| prev_year   = 2008\n| next_title  = The Henry Cow Box Redux: The Complete Henry Cow\n| next_year   = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set''''' (also known as '''''The Road''''') is a nine-[[Compact Disc|CD]] plus one-[[DVD]] limited edition<ref>1500 copies (box set liner notes).</ref> [[box set]] by [[England|English]] [[avant-rock]] [[Musical ensemble|group]] [[Henry Cow]], and was released by [[Recommended Records|R\u0113R Megacorp]] in January 2009. It consists of almost 10 hours of previously unreleased recordings made between 1972 and 1978 from concerts, radio broadcasts, one-off projects, events and the studio. Included are new compositions, over four hours of [[free improvisation]], and live performances of some of Henry Cow's original LP repertoire.\n\n[[Chris Cutler]], of Henry Cow and [[Recommended Records]], planned and coordinated the whole project. Assembly of the recordings began in the mid-1990s and were edited by Cutler. He also prepared and edited two books that are included in the box set. [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]] [[remaster]]ed and, where possible, non-invasively [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|remixed]] the original recordings at Studio Midi-Pyrenees in France between 2004 and 2008.\n\nThe box set was expected to be ready before the end of 2008 to coincide with the 40th anniversary of the formation of Henry Cow, but the discovery of additional material delayed its release. Volume 6 of the box set, ''[[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'' was released separately by R\u0113R Megacorp in September 2008 in advance of the box set's release. A limited edition bonus CD, ''A Cow Cabinet of Curiosities'' was given to subscribers of the box set.\n\nIn March 2017 Volumes 1 to 5 and 7 to 10 of the box set, plus the bonus CD were each released by R\u0113R Megacorp as separate albums.\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[All About Jazz]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=AllmusicP1/><ref name=AllmusicP2/>\n| rev3 = Dusted\n| rev3Score = favourable<ref name=Dusted/>\n}}\n{{Quote box | quote  = \"[This is] one of the best collections ever released about a group that most people have never heard.\" | source = John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]].<ref name=AllAboutJazz>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/the-40th-anniversary-henry-cow-box-set-by-john-kelman.php |title=Henry Cow: The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |website=[[All About Jazz]] |first=John |last=Kelman |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=24 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730211951/https://www.allaboutjazz.com/henry-cow-the-40th-anniversary-henry-cow-box-set-by-john-kelman.php |archivedate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> | width = 22em <!-- to match {{Album ratings}} -->| align  = right}}\n\nIn a review of this box set, John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]] said that it \"offers, for the first time, a comprehensive account of Henry Cow's breadth and depth.\" He went on to say that \"If ever there were a group with a wrong to be righted, it would have to be Henry Cow. With a wellspring of unreleased material, an impressive editing and mastering job that's made even audience cassette recordings sound crystal clear, ... ''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set'' is the set die-hard fans have been waiting for.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> This review was listed at position 3 in All About Jazz's \"Top 50 Most Recommended CD Reviews\" for 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/yearend_article_recommended.php?this_year=2009&article_type=100 |title=Top 50 Most Recommended CD Reviews: 2009 |website=[[All About Jazz]] |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] described the box set as a \"monument\" and a \"treasure trove\".<ref name=AllmusicP1>{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=the-road-vols-1-5-mw0001928009|pure_url=yes}} |title=Henry Cow: The Road, Vols. 1\u20135 |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Couture |accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> He said that it \"present[s] for the first time a complete picture of Henry Cow, from the rehearsal-intensive compositions to the ever-important improvisations, through all incarnations of the band and including both highs and lows.\"<ref name=AllmusicP2>{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=10-road-40th-anniversary-box-set-6-mw0001272127|pure_url=yes}} |title=Henry Cow: The Road, Vols. 6\u201310 |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Couture |accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> ''Dusted Magazine'' said that the set \"fills in many missing historical and compositional links\" and that it is a \"fitting monument to one of the most interesting and eclectic groups to come out of the 1970s.\"<ref name=Dusted>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/5258 |title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |last=Medwin |first=Marc |date=25 September 2009 |magazine=Dusted Magazine |accessdate=6 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124143/http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/5258 |archivedate=9 February 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe box set is split into two boxes:\n*Box 1: ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135'' consists of five CDs and a book, and covers the period 1972 to 1976. Included is the March 1976 [[Hamburg]] radio show that was [[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]]\u2019s last concert with the band, and the [[Trondheim]] concert that followed in May where Henry Cow improvised as a quartet in the dark.\n*Box 2: ''The Road: Volumes 6\u201310'' consists of four CDs, a DVD and a book, and covers the period 1976 to 1978. Included is the March 1978 [[Bremen]] radio broadcast and the May 1977 [[Sveriges Radio|Swedish Radio]] broadcast. The DVD is a 75 minute video of Henry Cow (with [[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] and [[Dagmar Krause]]) performing in Switzerland in 1976.\n\nSubscribers to this box set received a limited edition bonus CD, plus a third, empty box entitled ''The Studio: Volumes 1\u20135'' to hold the five Henry Cow studio recordings re-issued on CD by [[Recommended Records]] in the ''[[Henry Cow Box]]'' in 2006. Space was left in ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135'' box for the CD re-issue of ''[[Concerts (Henry Cow album)|Concerts]]'' (also included in the ''Henry Cow Box''). Combining the ''Henry Cow Box'' and ''The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set'' gives the complete works of Henry Cow.\n\n==Box 1: ''The Road: Volumes 1\u20135''==\nA 60-page book accompanies this box and contains the following:\n*Volumes 1\u20135 track notes\n*Memoirs by [[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]], [[Chris Cutler]], [[Geoff Leigh]], [[Lindsay Cooper]],{{refn|[[Lindsay Cooper]]'s contribution was taken from a collection of memoirs she had dictated to a friend between 1999 and 2001 when she could no longer use her hands due to [[multiple sclerosis]]. The notes were for a book she was working on at the time, ''The Road is Wider Than Long: Travels with MS''. [[Chris Cutler]] said that while this box set was being prepared, \"communication [with her] had become almost impossible.\"{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|pp=3,37}} Cooper died on 18 September 2013.<ref name=Fordham>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/24/lindsay-cooper |last=Fordham |first=John |title=Lindsay Cooper obituary |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 September 2013| accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Mack>{{cite web |url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/rip-lindsay-cooper-member-of-comus-and-henry-cow-collaborator |last=Mack |first=Shane |title=RIP: Lindsay Cooper, member of Comus and Henry Cow collaborator |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |date=19 September 2013| accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} [[Peter Blegvad]] and [[Dagmar Krause]]\n*Henry Cow concert list, May 1968 to August 1978{{refn|Compiled by Aymeric Leroy,<ref name=HC-chron/> and Chris Cutler.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=59}}|group=\"nb\"|name=\"HC-concerts\"}}\n----\n\n===''Volume 1: Beginnings''===\nExtracts from rehearsal and other tapes from before ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]'' (1973).\n\n\"Pre-Teenbeat I/II\" are fragments later incorporated into \"Teenbeat\". Track 6 is an extended version of \"Teenbeat\" with a lengthy guitar solo from Fred Frith and an embedded free improvisation section. \"Citizen King\" became \"[[Nine Funerals of the Citizen King]]\", and \"Nirvana for Moles\" became \"Nirvana for Mice\" on ''Legend''. \"Rapt in a Blanket\" and \"Came to See You\" are two songs composed and sung by Frith around arrangements by Henry Cow. Frith had presented the songs to the group as just chords and a tune and in need of elaboration, which forced the band to adjust their approach from only working on longish instrumentals. At the time Chris Cutler had been rehearsing part-time with Henry Cow, and he has stated that it was this new challenge which prompted him to join the group permanently.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=4}}\n\n''With the Yellow Half-Moon and Blue Star'' is a Frith composition that was commissioned by the Cambridge Contemporary Dance Group under Liebe Klug, and was named after a painting by [[Paul Klee]] (''Avec la demi-lune jaune et l'\u00e9toile bleue'').{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=7}} Only an extract of it appeared on ''Legend'', whereas it is featured here for the first time in its entirety. ''Guider Tells of Silent Airborne Machine'' is a suite of three instrumentals, \"Olwyn Grainger\" and \"Betty McGowan\" by the group and \"Lottie Hare\" (\"a neo-classical miniature\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>) by John Greaves. Its inspiration came from a news item that appeared on 23 August 1971 in ''[[The Times]]'' about a group of [[Girl Guiding and Girl Scouting|Girl Guide]] leaders, Olwyn Grainger, Lottie Hare and Betty McGowan who had reported witnessing a [[Unidentified flying object|UFO]].{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=9}}\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Pre-Teenbeat I\n| writer1 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 1:44\n| title2 = Pre-Teenbeat II\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 1:28\n| title3 = Rapt in a Blanket\n| writer3 = Frith\n| length3 = 5:06\n| title4 = Came to See You\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 6:43\n| title5 = Amygdala extract (pre-''Legend'' demo)\n| writer5 = [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 3:35\n| title6 = Teenbeat\n| writer6 = Frith\n| length6 = 10:19\n| title7 = [[Nine Funerals of the Citizen King|Citizen King]]\n| writer7 = Hodgkinson\n| length7 = 5:21\n| title8 = Nirvana for Moles\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 4:09\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''With the Yellow Half-Moon and Blue Star''\n| title9 = Introduction\n| writer9 = Frith\n| length9 = 0:46\n| title10 = Invocation\n| writer10 = Frith\n| length10 = 2:08\n| title11 = Demi-Lune Jaune\n| writer11 = Frith\n| length11 = 2:10\n| title12 = Three Little Steps\n| writer12 = Frith\n| length12 = 2:13\n| title13 = Red Riff\n| writer13 = Frith\n| length13 = 1:50\n| title14 = Chorale Flautando\n| writer14 = Frith\n| length14 = 1:51\n| title15 = Cycling over the Cliff\n| writer15 = Frith\n| length15 = 4:08\n| title16 = First Light\n| writer16 = Frith\n| length16 = 0:51\n}}{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Guider Tells of Silent Airborne Machine''\n| total_length = 64:22\n| title17 = Olwyn Grainger\n| writer17 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], Frith, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]], Hodgkinson\n| length17 = 2:24\n| title18 = Betty McGowan\n| writer18 = Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, [[Geoff Leigh|Leigh]]\n| length18 = 6:12\n| title19 = Lottie Hare\n| writer19 = Greaves\n| length19 = 1:24\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, piano (start of track 18)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, violin, voice (tracks 3,4)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar, piano (end of tracks 18,19), voice (tracks 7,18)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, melodica, clarinet, voice (track 7)\n*[[Geoff Leigh]] \u2013 tenor saxophone (tracks 1,2,5\u201319), flute (tracks 1,2,5\u201319), voice (tracks 7,9,16)\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Amanda Parsons]] \u2013 conversation (track 6)\n*[[Ann Rosenthal]] \u2013 conversation (track 6)\n*[[D.J. Perry]] \u2013 spoken passage (tracks 9,16)\n*[[Dave Stewart (keyboardist)|Dave Stewart]] \u2013 celeste (track 6), conversation (track 6)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1,2,5 are from rehearsal tapes, recorded by Jack Balchin before ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]''\n*Tracks 3,4,6 were recorded in London, 28 February 1972{{refn|This is a correction of what appears in the CD liner notes.|group=\"nb\"|name=\"LN-correc\"}}\n*Tracks 7,8,17\u201319 were recorded in London, 24 April 1973<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n*Tracks 9\u201316 were recorded in London, 17 October 1972<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n----\n\n===''Volume 2: 1974\u20135''===\nA collection of live performances from 1974 and 1975.\n\n''Halsteren'' is an instrumental suite that incorporates an early version of [[Tim Hodgkinson]]'s \"[[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' (1975). Recorded in [[Halsteren]] in September 1974 when Henry Cow was a quartet of Cutler, Frith, Greaves and Hodgkinson, Hodgkinson's unfinished instrumental is performed here in sections interspaced with improvisations by the group.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} Part of another performance of this suite also features in \"Groningen\" on ''[[Concerts (Henry Cow album)|Concerts]]'' (1976). Halsteren concert organiser Jan Smagge recounts in the box set booklets an anecdote where the band were approached by several people during an interval and asked whether they could play any songs by [[Mud (band)|Mud]], a contemporary mainstream pop act.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} ''Halsteren'' is followed here by \"Living in the Heart of the Beast\" from a Paris concert with [[Robert Wyatt]] in May 1975. It is the first live recording of the completed vocal version of the composition, and is sung by [[Dagmar Krause]], her first public appearance with the band,<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> with Wyatt accompanying her in the closing verses.\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Introduction\n| writer1 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length1 = 1:52\n| title2 = [[Ruins (instrumental)|Ruins]] I\n| writer2 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length2 = 6:35\n| title3 = Half Asleep, Half Awake\n| writer3 = [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]]\n| length3 = 4:11\n| title4 = Ruins II\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 0:59\n| title5 = Heron Shower over Hamburg\n| writer5 = Frith\n| length5 = 2:29\n| title6 = Nix\n| writer6 = \n| length6 = 0:06\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Halsteren'' <small>([[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], Frith, Greaves, [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]])</small>\n| title7 = Halsteren 1\n| writer7 = \n| length7 = 1:08\n| title8 = Solo 1\n| writer8 = Hodgkinson\n| length8 = 1:08\n| title9 = Solo Extension 1\n| writer9 = \n| length9 = 2:21\n| title10 = Halsteren 2\n| writer10 = \n| length10 = 1:24\n| title11 = Extension 1\n| writer11 = \n| length11 = 0:17\n| title12 = Halsteren 3\n| writer12 = \n| length12 = 0:52\n| title13 = First Suspension\n| writer13 = \n| length13 = 4:28\n| title14 = Extension 2\n| writer14 = \n| length14 = 2:58\n| title15 = Extension 3\n| writer15 = \n| length15 = 1:19\n| title16 = Solo 2\n| writer16 = Frith\n| length16 = 1:20\n| title17 = Solo Extension 2\n| writer17 = \n| length17 = 2:32\n| title18 = Halsteren 4\n| writer18 = \n| length18 = 0:17\n| title19 = Second Suspension\n| writer19 = \n| length19 = 2:34\n| title20 = Extension 4\n| writer20 = \n| length20 = 1:58\n| title21 = Solo 3\n| writer21 = \n| length21 = 0:49\n| title22 = Solo Extension 3\n| writer22 = Greaves\n| length22 = 3:17\n| title23 = Halsteren 5\n| writer23 = \n| length23 = 1:21\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 60:01\n| title24 = [[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\"\n#<li value=24>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 7\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 8\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 9\n| writer24 = Hodgkinson\n| length24 = 13:46\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 oboe (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), bassoon (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), piano (tracks 24\u201332)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, glass bowls and clatter (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), viola (tracks 1\u20135,24\u201332), piano (track 1,2), electric and acoustic guitars (tracks 7\u201323), prism (tracks 7\u201323), xylophone (tracks 24\u201332)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar, piano (track 3), clothes pegs (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet (tracks 7\u201323)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice (tracks 24\u201332)\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Robert Wyatt]] \u2013 voice (tracks 29,32)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20135 were recorded on the [[John Peel|John Peel Show]] in London, 25 April 1974; broadcast by the BBC 9 May 1974<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n*Tracks 7\u201323 are from a concert at the Verenigingsgebouw in [[Halsteren]], 26 September 1974, recorded by Jan Smagge on a stereo reel-to-reel\n*Tracks 24\u201332 are from a concert at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]], [[Paris]], 8 May 1975, with live mix by Sarah Greaves\n----\n\n===''Volume 3: Hamburg''===\nRecordings from Henry Cow's March 1976 [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], plus two songs with [[Robert Wyatt]] from concerts in Paris and Rome in May and June 1975, respectively.\n\n\"Fair as the Moon\", followed later by \"Terrible as an Army with Banners\" are based on \"[[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners]]\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' (1975), and became the longest lasting \"building block\" the band used in live performances.{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=12}} \"Nirvana for Rabbits\" is a rework of the Frith composition \"Nirvana for Mice\" from ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]'' (1973), while \"Ottawa Song\" is part of a longer suite Frith composed for the Ottawa Company, the rest of which never survived, except for fragments that appeared in \"Muddy Mouse\" and \"Muddy Mouth\" on Wyatt's solo album, ''[[Ruth Is Stranger Than Richard]]'' (1975).{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=13}} This performance of \"Ottawa Song\" also appears (by accident) on ''[[#Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg|Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'', but without the introductory bassoon solo. \"Gloria Gloom\" is from [[Matching Mole]]'s second album, ''[[Matching Mole's Little Red Record]]'' (1972). \"Hamburg 1\u20135\", \"Red Noise 10\" and \"A Heart\" are improvisations by the band, the last two titled at the request of NDR.{{refn|While Henry Cow generally left their improvisations untitled and referred to them by the venue they were performed at, some radio broadcasters requested that they be given titles.|group=\"nb\"|name=\"improv-titles\"}}<ref>Volume 3 CD liner notes.</ref> \"Hamburg 2\" includes a fragment from [[Slapp Happy]]'s song, \"A Little Something\".\n\nWyatt sings on \"Little Red Riding Hood Hit the Road\" from his solo album, ''[[Rock Bottom (album)|Rock Bottom]]'' (1974), and on \"We Did It Again\", a \"surprising and wackily absurdist\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> cover of the [[Soft Machine]] song from their debut album, ''[[The Soft Machine (Soft Machine album)|The Soft Machine]]'' (1968). The version of \"We Did It Again\" that appears on this CD is a combination of two different recordings of the same performance, one from an audience cassette recording with \"a lot of audience reaction, a lot of guitar, thin-sounding drums and bass, and only a faint echo of the vocals\", and one from the mixing desk with \"almost no guitar, but plenty of drums, bass, and vocals\".<ref name=BobDrake>{{cite web |url=http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/wavs/index.htm |title=Henry Cow 40th Anniversary Box Set remastering notes |first=Bob |last=Drake |authorlink=Bob Drake (musician) |accessdate=10 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220084306/http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/wavs/index.htm |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 67:44\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Fair as the Moon]]\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 6:01\n| title2 = Nirvana for Rabbits\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 4:48\n| title3 = Ottawa Song\n| writer3 = Cutler, Frith\n| length3 = 3:41\n| title4 = Twilight Bridge\n| writer4 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], Cutler, Frith, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length4 = 2:04\n| title5 = Gloria Gloom\n| writer5 = [[Robert Wyatt|Wyatt]], [[Bill MacCormick|McCormick]]\n| length5 = 2:17\n| title6 = Hamburg 1\n| writer6 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length6 = 4:15\n| title7 = Hamburg 2\n| writer7 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 3:27\n| title8 = Red Noise 10\n| writer8 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length8 = 3:16\n| title9 = Hamburg 3\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length9 = 5:30\n| title10 = Hamburg 4\n| writer10 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length10 = 2:40\n| title11 = Hamburg 5\n| writer11 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length11 = 5:25\n| title12 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Terrible as a