epared. The subject of the tapes were: Cooper \u2013 youth to old age; Hodgkinson \u2013 history of language; and Frith \u2013 history of Henry Cow. The tapes ran continuously and inaudibly throughout the duration of the show, but were made audible by their creators from time to time with a foot pedal, without knowing what part of the tape would be heard. Chris Cutler explained that it was an \"attempt to inhabit a dramaturgy anchored in narratives of origins, evolution, history and ritual\".{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=15}} They also decided to disguise and \"primitivise\" themselves and their equipment, and hence the darkness.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>{{sfn|Cutler|2009a|p=15}}\n\nFran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] called ''Trondheim'' the \"crown jewel\" of the box set, saying it was \"some of [Henry Cow's] darkest and most thrilling music\".<ref name=AllmusicP1/> John Kelman at [[All About Jazz]] described ''Trondheim'' as \"about as unapproachable as Henry Cow ever got, and yet amongst the densities and at times harsh realms are moments of profound beauty. The 80-minute improvisation ... demonstrates the kind of intuitive push-and-pull that could only come from musicians not just spending a great deal of time playing together, but also living together, with a potent ability to sometimes shift ambience and color at the drop of a dime.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| headline  = Disk 1\n| total_length = 48:25\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Trondheim I\"\n#<li value=1>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 7\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 8\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 9\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 10\n| writer1 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 48:25\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline  = Disk 2\n| total_length = 38:19\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Trondheim II\"\n#<li value=1>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 6\n| writer1 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length1 = 31:54\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith arr. [[Henry Cow]]\n| length7 = 6:25\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 oboe, bassoon, tapes, voice, flute (CD 1), recorder (CD 1), piano (CD 1, tracks 7\u20139), jaw harp (CD 2)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, telephone mouthpieces, amplification, flotsam (CD 1), voice (CD 1), jetsam (CD 2), piano (CD 2)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, 6-string bass guitar, xylophone, tapes, violin (CD 1), tubular bells (CD 1),\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, clarinet, voice, tapes, alto saxophone (CD 2), mbira (CD 2)\n\n====Track notes====\n*All tracks from a cassette recording made by Henry Cow at the mixing desk at a concert at Studentersamfundet, [[Trondheim]], 26 May 1976, mixed by Joel Schwartz\n\n==Box 2: ''The Road: Volumes 6\u201310''==\nA 60-page book accompanies this box and contains the following:\n*Volumes 6\u201310 track notes\n*Memoirs by [[Nick Hobbs]], [[Franco Fabbri]], [[Georgina Born]], [[Fred Frith]], [[Chris Wangro]] and [[Tim Hodgkinson]]\n*Post Henry Cow collaborations\n*A summary economic history of Henry Cow\n*Appendix 1: Equipment \u2013 PA system, studio, vehicles{{refn|Taken from documents written by Nick Hobbs that were included with Henry Cow's application for support from the [[Arts Council of Great Britain|Arts Council]].{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=19}}|group=\"nb\"}}\n*Appendix 2: 1977 Henry Cow accounts\n*Appendix 3: Extract from the Henry Cow Weekly Meeting Minute Book, 13 December 1976, [[Trappes]]\n----\n\n===''Volume 6: Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg''===\n{{main|Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg}}\n[[Sveriges Radio|Swedish Radio]] recordings of concerts performed in May 1976 in [[Gothenburg]] and May 1977 in [[Stockholm]]. This CD was released separately from the box set by R\u0113R Megacorp in September 2008.\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 63:23\n| title1 = Stockholm 1\n| writer1 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 6:38\n| title2 = [[Erk Gah]]\"\n#<li value=2>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\n| writer2 = Hodgkinson\n| length2 = 17:06\n:3:28\n:2:55\n:2:27\n:6:17\n:1:59\n| title7 = A Bridge to Ruins\n| writer7 = Hodgkinson\n| length7 = 5:08\n| title8 = Ottawa Song\n| writer8 = Cutler, Frith\n| length8 = 3:27\n| title9 = G\u00f6teborg 1\"\n#<li value=9>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length9 = 16:53\n:6:06\n:8:20\n:2:27\n| title12 = No More Songs\n| writer12 = [[Phil Ochs|Ochs]] arr. Frith\n| length12 = 3:35\n| title13 = Stockholm 2\n| writer13 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length13 = 6:13\n| title14 = March\n| writer14 = Frith\n| length14 = 4:15\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello (tracks 1\u20137,12\u201314)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, flute, recorder, piano (tracks 1\u20132), tapes (tracks 9-11)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, electrification, piano (track 10)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, xylophone, tapes (tracks 9-11), piano (tracks 13\u201314)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, voice (tracks 9-11), tapes (tracks 9-11)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 singing (tracks 1\u20137,12\u201314)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 bass guitar (track 8), voice (track 8)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20137 and 12\u201314 were recorded for ''Tonkraft'' by [[Sveriges Radio]] at a concert in [[Stockholm]] on 9 May 1977 and broadcast on 8 June and 11 June 1977; the programme producer was S. Vermalin\n*Track 8 was recorded for the [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop in [[Hamburg]] on 26 March 1976; its inclusion in this volume was unintentional and later acknowledged (see ''[[Stockholm & G\u00f6teborg]]'')\n*Tracks 9-11 were recorded for ''Tonkraft'' by Sveriges Radio at a concert in [[Gothenburg]] on 28 May 1976 and broadcast on 14 July and 17 July 1976; the programme producer was Christer Eklund\n----\n\n===''Volume 7: Later and Post-Virgin''===\nA collection of live performances from late 1976 and 1977.\n\n\"Joan\" and \"On Suicide\", traditionally associated with [[Art Bears]] and ''[[Hopes and Fears (Art Bears album)|Hopes and Fears]]'' (1978), feature here and show that they were Henry Cow songs long before Art Bears came into being.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"On Suicide\" is longer than the Art Bears version and ends with a cello solo by [[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]]; the [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]]/[[Hanns Eisler|Eisler]] song, arranged by [[Fred Frith]], had been suggested to the group by [[Anthony Moore]].{{sfn|Piekut|2019|pp=291\u2013292}} The Art Bears version of \"Joan\" also differs from the live recording here in that it is shorter (several sections are \"telescoped\" into one), and the lyrics are not the same. [[Chris Cutler]] wrote the original lyrics for \"Joan\" and [[Tim Hodgkinson]]'s \"The Pirate Song\", but the group were unhappy with them, and the songs were withdrawn from Henry Cow's repertoire. \"Joan\" was only performed a few times, and \"The Pirate Song\" not at all. Prior to Henry Cow's recording session at Sunrise in Switzerland in January 1978, Cutler rewrote the lyrics of the two songs, but once again there were objections from factions within the group. [[Dagmar Krause]], however, supported the new lyrics and both songs were recorded by Henry Cow with the revised texts, only to be  released later by Art Bears on ''Hopes and Fears'' as a result of further disagreements with the group.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=5}}\n\n\"Untitled Piece\" was a work-in-progress by [[Lindsay Cooper]] that was only performed a few times by Henry Cow,{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=6}} and foreshadowed some of her work that appeared later on her 1998 solo album ''A View From the Bridge''.<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"Chaumont 1\", \"Chaumont 2\" and \"March\" are from a Paris concert featuring an improvisation by the group, a bassoon and saxophone duet by Cooper and Hodgkinson, and Frith's familiar \"March\" to close the set. Also included are new renditions of \"Teenbeat\" and \"Bittern Storm over Ulm\". According to [[All About Jazz]], \"Teenbeat 2\" features \"some of Frith's most searing guitar playing of the box\", and \"Teenbeat 3\" has \"Hodgkinson's saxophone at its most visceral.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n\"Post-Teen Auditorium Invasion\" and \"Bucket Waltz\" are from a concert in [[Amsterdam]] that feature guests [[Annemarie Roelofs]] and ex-Henry Cow member [[Geoff Leigh]]. Roelofs, who was attending the concert, began playing trombone from the audience and was invited to join Henry Cow on stage. She ended up touring with the band the following year and playing on ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]''.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=43}} Leigh, whose band [[Red Balune]] was playing at the same concert, was invited by his former band to guest with them.<ref name=HC-chron/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 69:57\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Joan\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 5:26\n| title2 = Teenbeat 2\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 8:05\n| title3 = Would You Prefer Us to Lie?\n| writer3 = Cutler, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]]\n| length3 = 4:28\n| title4 = Untitled Piece\n| writer4 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length4 = 11:31\n| title5 = Chaumont 1\n| writer5 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], Cooper, Cutler, Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 9:01\n| title6 = Chaumont 2\n| writer6 = Cooper, Hodgkinson\n| length6 = 2:14\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith\n| length7 = 7:00\n| title8 = Brain Storm over Barnsley\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 3:23\n| title9 = Teenbeat 3\n| writer9 = Frith\n| length9 = 6:45\n| title10 = Post-Teen Auditorium Invasion\n| writer10 = Cooper, Hodgkinson, [[Geoff Leigh|Leigh]], [[Annemarie Roelofs|Roelofs]]\n| length10 = 3:56\n| title11 = Bucket Waltz\n| writer11 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, Leigh, Roelofs\n| length11 = 4:26\n| title12 = On Suicide\n| writer12 = [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]], [[Hanns Eisler|Eisler]]\n| length12 = 3:42\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet (track 12), voice (track 5), tapes\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, xylophone, tubular bells, violin, piano (track 7)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, jaw harp, flute, piano (tracks 3\u20135), accordion (track 5)\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice (track 1,3,7,12)\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, contact microphone amplification (tracks 5\u20137)\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Geoff Leigh]] \u2013 tenor saxophone (tracks 10\u201311)\n*[[Annemarie Roelofs]] \u2013 trombone (tracks 10\u201311)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20133 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Wandsworth Town Hall, [[London]], 13 February 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 4 was recorded on cassette from the audience at De Plek, [[Flushing, Netherlands|Vlissingen]], 22 May 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Tracks 5\u20137 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Salle des Fetes, Chaumont, 25 November 1976, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Tracks 8\u201311 were recorded on cassette from the audience at Melkweg, [[Amsterdam]], 16 December 1977, live mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 12 was from an unidentified cassette recording, probably May/June 1977\n----\n\n===''Volume 8: Bremen''===\nExtracts from a live radio broadcast on [[Radio Bremen]] for New Jazz Live on 22 March 1978.\n\nHenry Cow perform here as a [[quintet]] of Hodgkinson/Frith/Cooper/Born/Cutler; Dagmar Krause had left the band the previous November due to ill health.<ref name=HC-chron/> \"Armed Maniac/Things We Forgot\" is a titled improvisation with references \"in ambience\" to contemporary classical composers [[Krzysztof Penderecki]] and [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]].<ref group=\"nb\" name=improv-titles/><ref name=AllAboutJazz/> ''New Suite'' is a Fred Frith composition that includes \"Van Fleet\", a pun on [[Captain Beefheart|Don Van Vliet]],{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=368}} and an instrumental version of Tim Hodgkinson's \"Viva Pa Ubu\". \"Viva Pa Ubu\" is a song that had been recorded, with the whole group singing, during (what became) the ''[[Hopes and Fears (Art Bears album)|Hopes and Fears]]'' recording sessions in January 1978, and was the start of a musical production by Hodgkinson of [[Alfred Jarry]]'s play ''[[Ubu Roi]]'' (Pa Ubu being a character in the play).{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=11}} It was later released on the ''[[Recommended Records Sampler]]'' and re-released as a bonus track on the CD reissue of ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]''. ''Die Kunst Der Orgel'' is a 34-minute improvisation that ends with an instrumental version of Tim Hodgkinson's \"[[Erk Gah]]\".\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Armed Maniac/Things We Forgot\n| writer1 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]], [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length1 = 11:55\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''New Suite''\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title2 = Van Fleet\n| writer2 = Frith\n| length2 = 1:49\n| title3 = Viva Pa Ubu instrumental extract\n| writer3 = Hodgkinson\n| length3 = 4:35\n| title4 = The Big Tune Begins\n| writer4 = Frith\n| length4 = 0:45\n| title5 = The Big Tune Continues\n| writer5 = Frith\n| length5 = 2:11\n| title6 = The Big Tune Ends\n| writer6 = Frith\n| length6 = 1:30\n| title7 = March\n| writer7 = Frith\n| length7 = 3:46\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 74:00\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| headline = ''Die Kunst Der Orgel''\n| title8 = Bremen\"\n#<li value=8>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 5\n| writer8 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson\n| length8 = 34:25\n| title13 = Erk Gah instrumental extract\"\n:13{{ns|3}}\"Part 1\"\n:14{{ns|3}}\"Part 2\n| writer13 = Hodgkinson\n| length13 = 13:04\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, mbira, voice (track 9)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, tubular bells, marimba (track 8), xylophone (track 14), violin, piano (track 7)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, sopranino saxophone, recorder, piano (tracks 9\u201311,14), accordion, egg-slicer\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums, marimba (tracks 9\u201310), piano (tracks 1,14)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Recorded for New Jazz Live at a public concert at Sendesall, Studio F, [[Radio Bremen]], 22 March 1978, produced by Bernd Meier, concert mix by Jack Balchin\n----\n\n===''Volume 9: Late''===\nA collection of performances from June and July 1978, plus Henry Cow's set at the inaugural [[Rock in Opposition|Rock in Opposition Festival]] in March 1978.\n\n\"Joy of Sax\" is a saxophone trio of Lindsay Cooper, Tim Hodgkinson and David Chambers from [[the Orckestra]], which was a merger of Henry Cow, the [[Mike Westbrook]] Brass Band and folk singer [[Frankie Armstrong]] that took place in 1977. \"Jackie-ing\", also featuring Chambers, is a Westbrook arrangement of a [[Thelonious Monk]] composition that the Orckestra had performed. \"The Herring People\" is a Fred Frith instrumental he wrote to \"counterbalance\" the increasingly complex Hodgkinson and Cooper compositions.{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=9}} It was later recorded by Henry Cow during the July and August 1978 ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]'' sessions, but was only released for the first time, as \"Waking Against Sleep\", on the 1990 CD re-issue of Frith's solo album, ''[[Gravity (Fred Frith album)|Gravity]]'' (1980).{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=8}} It was also recorded by [[Curlew (band)|Curlew]] under the title \"Time and a Half\", and appeared on their album, ''North America'' (1985), which was produced by Frith.\n\nThe improvisation \"RIO\" and Cooper's \"Half the Sky\" was Henry Cow's set at the inaugural [[Rock in Opposition]] (RIO) festival that took place on 12 March 1978 at the [[New London Theatre]]. RIO was a collective of \"[[progressive rock|progressive]]\" bands that were united in their opposition to the [[music industry]]. Henry Cow initiated the movement and the other inaugural members, who also performed at the concert, were [[Stormy Six]] (Italy), [[Samla Mammas Manna]] (Sweden), [[Univers Zero]] (Belgium) and [[Etron Fou Leloublan]] (France). ''Dusted Magazine'' described Henry Cow's \"RIO\" improvisation at this event as \"one of their most cacophonous and cataclysmic\".<ref name=Dusted/>\n\nCooper's \"Half the Sky\", which had been recorded in January 1978 at Sunrise in Switzerland and was later released on ''Western Culture'', was named for [[Mao Zedong|Chairman Mao]]'s dictum \"Women hold up half the sky\".{{sfn|Cutler|2009b|p=8}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/GCA-Olympics/idUSSYD20777320080811|title=For Chen, women hold up half the sky|last=Hardach|first=Sophie|date=11 August 2008|website=Reuters|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref> \"Virgins of Illinois\" is another piece from the Brass Band's repertoire, and is a medley of several English folk songs that becomes a \"broad dance in three\".{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=375}} Piekut noted that the recording of \"Virgins of Illinois\" on this disc is not the complete piece as it was performed live \u2013 it stops before the song's main tune begins.{{sfn|Piekut|2019|p=375}}{{sfn|Piekut|2019|loc=p. 445 (Chapter 8, footnote 70)}}\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 35:29\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Joy of Sax\n| writer1 = \n| length1 = 3:50\n| title2 = Jackie-ing\n| writer2 = [[Thelonious Monk|Monk]] arr. [[Mike Westbrook|Westbrook]]\n| length2 = 1:15\n| title3 = Untitled 2\n| writer3 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]]\n| length3 = 1:32\n| title4 = The Herring People\n| writer4 = [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length4 = 2:07\n| title5 = RIO\"\n#<li value=5>{{ns|2}}\"Part 1\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 2\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 3\"\n#{{ns|2}}\"Part 4\n| writer5 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], Cooper, [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length5 = 17:09\n| title9 = Half the Sky\n| writer9 = Cooper\n| length9 = 5:05\n| title10 = Virgins of Illinois\n| writer10 = trad.\n| length10 = 2:13\n| title11 = Viva Pa Ubu\n| writer11 = Hodgkinson\n| length11 = 2:18\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet, voice (track 7)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, violin, xylophone\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, recorder, sopranino saxophone\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums\n\n=====Guests=====\n*[[Annemarie Roelofs]] \u2013 trombone (tracks 4,10)\n*[[Dave Chambers (musician)|Dave Chambers]] \u2013 saxophone (tracks 1,2)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1\u20134,10 are from an audience recording commonly believed to be from the Festa del PdUP (Partito di Unit\u00e0 Proletaria) in Monza, Italy, 9 July 1978, though this is disputed by Chris Cutler; live concert mix by E. M. Thomas<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>; also 'disputable' is track 4, \"The Herring People\", which is believed to be an alternate mix (less reverb) of the recording \"Waking Against Sleep\" on the CD reissue [[Fred Frith]]'s ''[[Gravity (Fred Frith album)|Gravity]]'' (cd ESD 1990), credited as a studio recording from the ''[[Western Culture (album)|Western Culture]]'' sessions (see this [[Talk:Henry Cow discography#\"Waking Against Sleep\"|talk page]]){{Citation required|date=January 2017}}\n*Tracks 5\u20139 are from the [[Rock in Opposition]] Festival at [[New London Theatre]], [[Drury Lane]], [[London]], 12 March 1978, recorded by Hasse Bruniusson of [[Samla Mammas Manna]], live concert mix by Jack Balchin\n*Track 11 was recorded on cassette from the audience at [[Cervia]], 23 July 1978, live concert mix by E. M. Thomas\n----\n\n===''Volume 10: Vevey'' (DVD)===\nA 75-minute video of Henry Cow performing in [[Vevey]], [[Switzerland]] in August 1976, recorded for the Swiss TV program, ''Kaleidospop''.<ref name=HC-chron>{{cite web |url=http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/bands/chrono/henrycow.html |title=Henry Cow chronology |website=Calyx: The Canterbury Music Website |accessdate=9 July 2008}}</ref> This is the only known video recording of Henry Cow.<ref name=AllmusicP2/><ref>Volume 10 DVD liner notes.</ref>\n\nThe DVD features the group live outdoors on the grass and playing a set that was representative from the time. It includes [[Tim Hodgkinson]]'s two \"epic\" compositions, \"[[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\" and \"[[Erk Gah]]\", and two improvisations, \"Vevey 1\" and \"Vevey 2\".<ref name=AllAboutJazz/> \"Beautiful As ...\", followed later by \"Terrible As ...\" are based on \"[[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners]]\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' (1975). Fran\u00e7ois Couture at [[AllMusic]] described the multi-camera work on the DVD as \"pretty good\" and the editing \"dated\", but added that \"seeing the band in action, both navigating through its most complex material and engaging in collective improvisation, is quite an experience.\"<ref name=AllmusicP2/>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 74:48\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Beautiful As ...]]\n| writer1 = [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 6:50\n| title2 = Vevey 1\n| writer2 = [[Georgina Born|Born]], [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], Cutler, Frith, [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]], [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length2 = 8:49\n| title3 = [[Beautiful as the Moon \u2013 Terrible as an Army with Banners|Terrible As ...]]\n| writer3 = Cutler, Frith\n| length3 = 2:19\n| title4 = \n| note4 = Tim speaks\n| writer4 = \n| length4 = 1:04\n| title5 = No More Songs\n| writer5 = [[Phil Ochs|Ochs]] arr. Frith\n| length5 = 3:48\n| title6 = [[Living in the Heart of the Beast]]\n| writer6 = Hodgkinson\n| length6 = 16:57\n| title7 = Vevey 2\n| writer7 = Born, Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 13:51\n| title8 = March\n| writer8 = Frith\n| length8 = 2:42\n| title9 = [[Erk Gah]]\n| writer9 = Hodgkinson\n| length9 = 18:28\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Georgina Born|Georgie Born]] \u2013 bass guitar, cello\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 bassoon, oboe, recorder, sopranino saxophone, piccolo, piano\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar, violin, xylophone, piano, tubular bells\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 organ, alto saxophone, clarinet\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 voice\n\n====Track notes====\n*Recorded 25 August 1976, [[Vevey]], [[Switzerland]], concert mixed by Joel Schwartz\n\n==Bonus CD==\n===''A Cow Cabinet of Curiosities''===\nA limited edition<ref>1000 copies (bonus CD liner notes).</ref> CD given to subscribers of the box set. The title alludes to the name of [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]]'s band, Cabinet of Curiosities.\n\n\"Pre Virgin Demo 1/2\" include fragments that were later incorporated into tracks on ''[[Legend (Henry Cow album)|Legend]]''. \"Lovers of Gold\" is an alternate version of \"Beginning: The Long March\" from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' that was created by [[Chris Cutler]].<ref name=discog/> \"The Glove\" is derived from raw material recorded during the ''[[Unrest (Henry Cow album)|Unrest]]'' sessions.<ref name=discog>{{Cite web|url=http://nyds-discographies.com/frith.htm |title=Discography of Fred Frith |website=New York Downtown Scene and Other Miscellaneous Discographies |author1=Ramond, Michel |author2=Roussel, Patrice |author3=Vuilleumier, Stephane |accessdate=29 May 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619155344/http://nyds-discographies.com/frith.htm |archivedate=19 June 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Track list====\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 55:17\n| title_width = 40%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| title1 = Pre Virgin Demo 1\n| writer1 = mostly [[Fred Frith|Frith]]\n| length1 = 3.55\n| title2 = Pre Virgin Demo 2\n| writer2 = mostly [[Tim Hodgkinson|Hodgkinson]]\n| length2 = 1:02\n| title3 = Unidentified Improvisation 1\n| writer3 = [[Lindsay Cooper|Cooper]], [[Chris Cutler|Cutler]], Frith, [[John Greaves (musician)|Greaves]], Hodgkinson\n| length3 = 1:30\n| title4 = Unidentified Improvisation 2\n| writer4 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, [[Dagmar Krause|Krause]]\n| length4 = 5:37\n| title5 = Unidentified late composition\n| writer5 = probably Cooper\n| length5 = 2:04\n| title6 = Exploded Amygdala/Teen Introduction\n| writer6 = Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, [[Geoff Leigh|Leigh]]\n| length6 = 3:37\n| title7 = Lovers of Gold\n| writer7 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length7 = 6:29\n| title8 = Hamburg 6\n| writer8 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length8 = 5:33\n| title9 = [[Ruins (instrumental)|Ruins]] extract\n| writer9 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length9 = 8:24\n| title10 = Hamburg 7\n| writer10 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson, Krause\n| length10 = 9:44\n| title11 = Half the Sky\n| writer11 = Cooper\n| length11 = 5:03\n| title12 = Extract from The Glove\n| writer12 = Cooper, Cutler, Frith, Greaves, Hodgkinson\n| length12 = 2:19\n}}\n\n====Personnel====\n*[[Chris Cutler]] \u2013 all tracks, piano (track 10), voice (track 12)\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013  all tracks, voice (track 12)\n*[[Tim Hodgkinson]] \u2013 all tracks, voice (track 12)\n*[[John Greaves (musician)|John Greaves]] \u2013 tracks 1\u201310,12, voice (track 12)\n*[[Geoff Leigh]] \u2013 tracks 1,2,6, voice (track 1)\n*[[Lindsay Cooper]] \u2013 tracks 3\u20135,7\u201312, voice (track 12)\n*[[Dagmar Krause]] \u2013 tracks 4,8\u201310\n*[[Peter Blegvad]] \u2013 clarinet (track 7)\n*[[Anthony Moore]] \u2013 mounted and amplified tuning forks (track 7)\n\n====Track notes====\n*Tracks 1,2 were recorded in Henry Cow's rehearsal space by Jack Balchin, probably 1972\n*Tracks 3\u20136 were extracted from a forgotten tape from 1975\u201377 which surfaced while this box set was being compiled<ref group=\"nb\" name=LN-correc/>\n*Track 7 is an out-take from ''[[In Praise of Learning]]'' mixed by Tim Hodgkinson at Cold Storage in 1984; previously issued on the 1991 CD (remixed) edition of ''In Praise of Learning''\n*Tracks 8\u201310 were recorded at a public concert for [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] Jazz Workshop, [[Hamburg]], 26 March 1976\n*Track 11 recorded at a public concert at Sendesaal, Studio F, [[Radio Bremen]], 22 March 1978, produced by Bernd Meier\n*Track 12 is an extract from an ''[[Unrest (Henry Cow album)|Unrest]]'' out-take mixed by Tim Hodgkinson at Cold Storage in 1984; previously issued in full (6:35) on the 1991 CD edition of ''Unrest''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite AV media notes| title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |others=[[Henry Cow]] |year=2009a |chapter=The Road: Volumes 1\u20135 |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Cutler |editor-link=Chris Cutler |type=box set booklet |publisher=[[Recommended Records]] |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes| title=The 40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set |others=Henry Cow |year=2009b |chapter=The Road: Volumes 6\u201310 |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Cutler |type=box set booklet |publisher=Recommended Records |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Piekut |first=Benjamin |title=Henry Cow: The World Is a Problem |title-link=Henry Cow: The World Is a Problem |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |year=2019 |isbn=978-1-47800-405-9 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|2530314|The Road: Volumes 1\u20135|type=album}}\n*{{Discogs release|1800562|The Road: Volumes 6\u201310 With DVD|type=album}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120220084240/http://www.bordebasse.fr/henrycow/remastering.htm Henry Cow 40th Anniversary Box Set remastering notes] (including booklet corrections) by [[Bob Drake (musician)|Bob Drake]].\n*[http://www.cloudsandclocks.net/interviews/CC_interview08.html Interview with Chris Cutler on the box set (2008)]. Clouds and Clocks.\n*[http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/lyrics/henrycow/01.html Henry Cow lyrics]. Calyx: The Canterbury Website.\n\n{{Henry Cow|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:40th Anniversary Henry Cow Box Set, The}}\n[[Category:2009 live albums]]\n[[Category:2009 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Henry Cow albums]]\n[[Category:Recommended Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Recommended Records compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Live free improvisation albums]]\n", "name_user": "Bruce1ee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:reduced overlinking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_40th_Anniversary_Henry_Cow_Box_Set"}
